\"|'''4,534,008'''|| style=\"background:white;\"|\n| style=\"background:beige;\"|'''1,362,002'''|| style=\"background:beige;\"|\n|- \n| style=\"text-align:center\" | ''% of SA''||\n|''80.48%''||\n|''8.79%''||\n|''8.25%''||\n|''2.48%''||\n|}\n\n===Fertility rate (The Demographic Health Survey)===\nFertility rate (TFR) (Wanted Fertility Rate) and CBR (Crude Birth Rate):<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dhsprogram.com/|title=The DHS Program - Quality information to plan, monitor and improve population, health, and nutrition programs|website=Dhsprogram.com|accessdate=29 August 2017}}</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! style=\"width:50pt;\"| Year\n! style=\"width:50pt;\"| CBR (Total)\n! style=\"width:50pt;\"| TFR (Total)\n! style=\"width:50pt;\"| CBR (Urban)\n! style=\"width:50pt;\"| TFR (Urban)\n! style=\"width:50pt;\"| CBR (Rural)\n! style=\"width:50pt;\"| TFR (Rural)\n|-\n| 1998\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"| 21.90\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"| 2.90 (2.3)\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"| 19.2\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"| 2.25 (1.8)\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"| 25.4\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"| 3.92 (2.9)\n|-\n| 2016\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"| 22.3\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"| 2.6 (2.0)\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"| 21.9\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"| 2.4 (1.9)\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"| 23.1\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"| 3.1 (2.4)\n|-\n|}\n\nFertility rate (TFR) (Wanted Fertility Rate) by ethnic group.\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! style=\"width:50pt;\"| Year\n! style=\"width:50pt;\"| Total\n! style=\"width:50pt;\"| Black African\n! style=\"width:50pt;\"| White\n! style=\"width:50pt;\"| Coloured\n! style=\"width:50pt;\"| Indian/Asian\n|-\n| 1998\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"| 2.9 (2.3)\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"| 3.1 (2.4)\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"| 1.9 (1.5)\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"| 2.5 (2.1)\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"| \n|-\n| 2016\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"| 2.6 (2.0)\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"| 2.7 (2.1)\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"| 1.5 (1.2)\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"| 2.5 (1.9)\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"| 1.7 (1.6)\n|-\n|}\n\n===Life expectancy===\nLife expectancy from 1950 to 2020 (''UN World Population Prospects'')<ref>{{cite web|title=World Population Prospects \u2013 Population Division \u2013 United Nations|periodical=|publisher=|url=https://esa.un.org/unpd/wpp/DataQuery/|format=|accessdate=2017-07-15|last=|date=|year=|month=|day=|language=|pages=|quote=|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160919061238/https://esa.un.org/unpd/wpp/DataQuery/|archive-date=19 September 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref>:\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n!Period\n!Life expectancy<br>(years)\n|-\n|1950\u20131955\n| 48.5\n|-\n|1955\u20131960\n|{{increase}} 51.3\n|-\n|1960\u20131965\n|{{increase}} 53.0\n|-\n|1965\u20131970\n|{{increase}} 54.8\n|-\n|1970\u20131975\n|{{increase}} 56.7\n|-\n|1975\u20131980\n|{{increase}} 57.3\n|-\n|1980\u20131985\n|{{increase}} 58.4\n|-\n|1985\u20131990\n|{{increase}} 61.0\n|-\n|1990\u20131995\n|{{increase}} 62.3\n|-\n|1995\u20132000\n|{{decrease}} 59.2\n|-\n|2000\u20132005\n|{{decrease}} 53.8\n|-\n|2005\u20132010\n|{{decrease}} 53.1\n|-\n|2010\u20132015\n|{{increase}} 59.5\n|-\n|2015\u20132020\n|{{increase}} 63.7\n|}\n\n==Ethnic groups==\n{{main article|Ethnic groups in South Africa}}\n[[File:South Africa dominant population group map.svg|thumb|Dominant population groups in South Africa. {{clear}} {{legend|#fb8072|Black African}} {{legend|#8dd3c7|Coloured}} {{legend|#80b1d3|Indian or other Asian}} {{legend|#ffffb3|White}} {{legend|#bebada|None dominant}}]]\n{{Pie chart\n| thumb = right under\n| caption = Ethnic groups South Africa (1911)\n| other = \n| label1 = [[Bantu peoples in South Africa|Black African]]\n| value1 = 67\n| color1 = Red\n| label2 = [[White South Africans|White]]\n| value2 = 21\n| color2 = Blue\n| label3 = [[Cape Coloureds|Coloured]] \n| value3 = 9\n| color3 = Purple \n| label4 = [[Asian South Africans|Asian]]\n| value4 = 3\n| color4 = Yellow\n}}\n{{Pie chart\n| thumb = right under\n| caption = Ethnic groups South Africa (2004)\n| other = \n| label1 = [[Bantu peoples in South Africa|Black African]]\n| value1 = 79\n| color1 = Red\n| label2 = [[White South Africans|White]]\n| value2 = 10\n| color2 = Blue\n| label3 = [[Cape Coloureds|Coloured]] \n| value3 = 9\n| color3 = Purple \n| label4 = [[Asian South Africans|Asian]]\n| value4 = 2\n| color4 = Yellow\n}}\n[[Statistics South Africa]] asks people to describe themselves in the census in terms of five [[Race (classification of human beings)|racial]] population groups.<ref>{{cite news|last=Lehohla|first=Pali|title=Debate over race and censuses not peculiar to SA|url=http://www.statssa.gov.za/news_archive/05may2005_1.asp|date=5 May 2005|newspaper=Business Report|accessdate=25 August 2013|quote=Others pointed out that the repeal of the Population Registration Act in 1991 removed any legal basis for specifying 'race'. The Identification Act of 1997 makes no mention of race. On the other hand, the Employment Equity Act speaks of 'designated groups' being 'black people, women and people with disabilities'. The Act defines 'black' as referring to 'Africans, coloureds and Indians'. Apartheid and the racial identification which underpinned it explicitly linked race with differential access to resources and power. If the post-apartheid order was committed to remedying this, race would have to be included in surveys and censuses, so that progress in eradicating the consequences of apartheid could be measured and monitored. This was the reasoning that led to a 'self-identifying' question about 'race' or 'population group' in both the 1996 and 2001 population censuses, and in Statistics SA's household survey programme.|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070814143522/http://www.statssa.gov.za/news_archive/05may2005_1.asp|archivedate=14 August 2007|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The [[South African National Census of 2011|2011 census]] figures for these groups were [[Bantu peoples in South Africa|Black African]] at 80.2%, [[White South Africans|White]] at 8.4%, [[Cape Coloureds|Coloured]] at 8.8%, [[Indian South Africans|Indian]]/[[Asian South Africans|Asian]] at 2.5%, and Other/Unspecified at 0.5%.<ref name=\"CIATONGA\">{{cite web|url= https://www.cia.gov/library/publications/the-world-factbook/geos/sf.html|title= Africa :: SOUTH AFRICA|publisher= CIA The World Factbook}}</ref>\n\nThe white percentage of the population has sharply declined. The first census in South Africa in 1911 showed that whites made up 22% of the population. This declined to 16% in 1980,<ref>{{Cite book | author=Study Commission on U.S. Policy toward Southern Africa (U.S.) | title = South Africa: time running out : the report of the Study Commission on U.S. Policy Toward Southern Africa  | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=sq43lnbklEUC&pg=PA42&dq#v=onepage&q=&f=false | publisher=University of California Press | year = 1981 | page = 42 | isbn = 0-520-04547-5}}</ref> and 8.9% in 2011.<ref name=Census2011>{{cite book |title=Census 2011: Census in brief |url=http://www.statssa.gov.za/census/census_2011/census_products/Census_2011_Census_in_brief.pdf|publisher=Statistics South Africa |location=Pretoria |year=2012 |isbn=9780621413885}}</ref>{{rp|21}}\n\n==Languages==\n{{Main article|Languages of South Africa}}\nSouth Africa has eleven [[official language]]s:<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fs.gov.za/Departments/SAC/Library/DEPART/lang_legislation1.htm |title=Constitution of South Africa, Chapter 1, Section 6 |publisher=Fs.gov.za |accessdate=30 May 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090729134936/http://www.fs.gov.za/Departments/SAC/Library/DEPART/lang_legislation1.htm |archivedate=29 July 2009 }}</ref> [[IsiZulu]]<ref name=\"CIATONGA\"/> 22.7%, [[IsiXhosa]]<ref name=\"CIATONGA\"/>  16%, [[Afrikaans]]<ref name=\"CIATONGA\"/>   13.5%, [[English language|English]] <ref name=\"CIATONGA\"/>  9.6%, [[Sepedi language|Sepedi]] <ref name=\"CIATONGA\"/>  9.1%, [[Setswana]]<ref name=\"CIATONGA\"/>  8%, [[Sesotho]]<ref name=\"CIATONGA\"/> 7.6%, [[Xitsonga]]<ref name=\"CIATONGA\"/>  4.5%, [[siSwati]]<ref name=\"CIATONGA\"/> 2.5%, [[Tshivenda]]<ref name=\"CIATONGA\"/> 2.4% and  [[isiNdebele]]<ref name=\"CIATONGA\"/> 2.1%.\n\nIn this regard it is third only to [[Bolivia]] and [[Official languages of India|India]] in number. While all the languages are formally equal, some languages are spoken more than others. According to the [[South African National Census of 2011|2011 census]], the three most spoken first languages are Zulu (22.7%), Xhosa (16.0%), and Afrikaans (13.5%).<ref name=Census2011/>{{rp|23\u201325}} Despite the fact that English is recognised as the language of commerce and science, it ranked fourth, and was spoken by only 9.6% of South Africans as a first language in 2011.<ref name=Census2011/>{{rp|23\u201325}}\n\nThe country also recognises several unofficial languages, including [[Makholokoe Tribes|Sekholokoe]], [[Fanagalo language|Fanagalo]], [[Khoe language|Khoe]], [[Lobedu language|Lobedu]], [[Nama language|Nama]], [[Northern Ndebele language|Northern Ndebele]], [[Phuthi language|Phuthi]], [[San language|San]] and [[South African Sign Language]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mediaclub.co.za/landstatic/80-languages|title=The languages of South Africa|last=|first=|date=December 2011|website=Media Club South Africa|publisher=Brand South Africa|accessdate=24 November 2017}}</ref> These unofficial languages may be used in certain official uses in limited areas where it has been determined that these languages are prevalent. Nevertheless, their populations are not such that they require nationwide recognition.\n\nMany of the \"unofficial languages\" of the San and Khoikhoi people contain regional dialects stretching northwards into Namibia and Botswana, and elsewhere. These people, who are a physically distinct population from other Africans, have their own cultural identity based on their hunter-gatherer societies. They have been marginalised to a great extent, and many of their languages are in danger of becoming [[Extinct language|extinct]].\n\nMany white South Africans also speak other European languages, such as Portuguese (also spoken by black [[Angola]]ns and [[Mozambique|Mozambicans]]), German, and Greek, while some Indians and other Asians in South Africa speak South Asian languages, such as Tamil, Hindi, Gujarati, [[Urdu language|Urdu]] and Telugu. Although many South Africans are of Huguenot (French) origin, South African French is spoken by fewer than 10,000 individuals country-wide. Congolese French is also spoken in South Africa by migrants.\n\nThe primary sign language of [[deafness|deaf]] South Africans is [[South African Sign Language]]. Other sign languages among indigenous peoples are also used.\n\n===By ethnicity===\nIn 2011, the first language was [[Zulu language|Zulu]] for 28.1% of african residents, [[Xhosa language|Xhosa]] for 19.8%, [[Northern Sotho language|Northern Sotho]] for 11.2%, [[Tswana language|Tswana]] for 9.7%, [[Sesotho language|Sesotho]] for 9.3%, [[Tsonga language|Tsonga]] for  5.5%, [[Swati language|Swati]] for 3.1%, [[Venda language|Venda]] for 2.9%, English for  2.8%, [[Southern Ndebele language|Southern Ndebele]] for  2.6%, [[Afrikaans]] for 1.5%, while 3.4% had another first language.<ref name=superweb>{{cite web|title=Community profiles > Census 2011 |url=http://interactive.statssa.gov.za/superweb |publisher=Statistics South Africa Superweb |accessdate=21 August 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130930103145/http://interactive.statssa.gov.za/superweb/ |archivedate=30 September 2013 |df=dmy }}</ref>\n\nAmong whites, Afrikaans was the first language for 59.1% of the population, compared to 35.0% for English. Other languages accounted for the remaining 5.9%.<ref name=superweb/>\n\n==Religion==\n{{Main article|Religion in South Africa}}\nAccording to the 2001 national census, [[Christianity in South Africa|Christians]] accounted for 79.7% of the population. This includes [[Protestantism in South Africa|Protestant]] (36.6%), [[Zionist Christian]] (11.1%), [[Pentecostalism|Pentecostal]]/[[Charismatic movement|Charismatic]] (8.2%), [[Roman Catholicism in South Africa|Roman Catholic]] (7.1%), [[Methodist Church of Southern Africa|Methodist]] (6.8%), [[Nederduits Gereformeerde Kerk|Dutch Reformed]] (6.7%), [[Anglican Church of Southern Africa|Anglican]] (3.8%); members of other Christian churches accounted for another 36% of the population. [[Islam in South Africa|Muslims]] accounted for 1.5% of the population, Other 2.3%, and 1.4% were Unspecified and None 15.1%.<ref name=\"CIATONGA\"/>\n\n[[African Indigenous Churches]] made up the largest of the Christian groups. Some believe that many people claiming no affiliation with any organised religion adhered to [[African traditional religion|traditional indigenous religions]]. Many people have [[Syncretism|syncretic]] religious practices combining Christian and indigenous influences.<ref name=\"DoS\">{{cite web|url=https://2001-2009.state.gov/g/drl/rls/irf/2006/71325.htm|title=South Africa|website=State.gov|accessdate=29 August 2017}}</ref>\n\n[[Islam in South Africa|Muslims]] are largely found among the [[Coloured]] and [[Indian South African|Indian]] ethnic groups. They have been joined by black or white South African converts as well as immigrants from other parts of Africa.<ref name=csmonitor/> South African Muslims claim that their faith is the fastest-growing religion of conversion in the country, with the number of black Muslims growing sixfold, from 12 000 in 1991 to 74 700 in 2004<ref name=csmonitor>{{cite web|url=http://www.csmonitor.com/2002/0110/p13s1-woaf.html|title=In South Africa, many blacks convert to Islam|website=Csmonitor.com|accessdate=29 August 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.religionnewsblog.com/9398/muslims-say-their-faith-growing-fast-in-africa |title=Muslims say their faith growing fast in Africa |publisher=Religionnewsblog.com |accessdate=7 November 2010}}</ref>\n\nThe Hindu population has its roots in the British colonial period, but later waves of immigration from India have also contributed to it. Most Hindus are of South Asian origin, but there are many who come from mixed racial stock. Some are converts due to the efforts of [[International Society for Krishna Consciousness|ISKCON]].\n\nOther minority religions in South Africa are [[Sikhism]], [[Jainism]] and [[Bah\u00e1'\u00ed Faith in South Africa|Bah\u00e1'\u00ed Faith]].<ref name=\"state.gov\">{{cite web|url=https://2001-2009.state.gov/g/drl/rls/irf/2005/51496.htm|title=South Africa \u2013 Section I. Religious Demography|publisher=U.S. Department of State|accessdate=15 July 2006}}</ref>\n\n===By ethnicity===\n87.9% of Black residents are Christian, 9.5% have [[Irreligion|no religion]], 0.2% are Muslim, 0.0% are Jewish, 1.22% are [[Hinduism|Hindu]] and 2.3% have other or undetermined beliefs.\n\n71.8% of White residents are Christian, 23.8% have [[Irreligion|no religion]], 0.2% are Muslim, 1.4% are Jewish, and 0.0% are [[Hinduism|Hindu]]. 2.7% have other or undetermined beliefs.\n\n==Other demographic statistics==\nDemographic statistics according to the World Population Review in 2019.<ref name=\"WPR 2019\">{{cite|url=http://worldpopulationreview.com/countries/south-africa-population/|title=South Africa Population 2019|website=World Population Review|access-date=6 April 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190403021136/http://worldpopulationreview.com/countries/south-africa-population/|archive-date=3 April 2019|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n*One birth every 27 seconds\t\n*One death every 58 seconds\t\n*One net migrant every 9 minutes\t\n*Net gain of one person every 47 seconds\n\nThe following demographic are from the [[CIA World Factbook]]<ref name=\".cia.gov\">{{cite|url=https://www.cia.gov/library/publications/the-world-factbook/geos/sf.html|title= The World FactBook - South Africa|date=July 12, 2018|work=[[The World Factbook]]}}{{PD-notice}}</ref> unless otherwise indicated.\n\n===Population===\n:55,380,210 (July 2018 est.)\n\n===Age structure===\n[[File:South Africapop.svg|thumb|350px|Population pyramid of South Africa in 2017]]\n:''0-14 years:'' 28.18% (male 7,815,651 /female 7,793,261)\n:''15-24 years:'' 17.24% (male 4,711,480 /female 4,837,897)\n:''25-54 years:'' 42.05% (male 11,782,848 /female 11,503,831)\n:''55-64 years:'' 6.71% (male 1,725,034 /female 1,992,035)\n:''65 years and over:'' 5.81% (male 1,351,991 /female 1,866,182) (2018 est.)\n\n===Median age===\n:total: 27.4 years. Country comparison to the world: 144th\n:male: 27.2 years \n:female: 27.6 years (2018 est.)\n\n===Birth rate===\n:109.9 births/1,000 population (2018 est.) Country comparison to the world: 78th\n\n===Death rate===\n:9.3 deaths/1,000 population (2018 est.) Country comparison to the world: 57th\n\n===[[Total fertility rate]]===\n:2.26 children born/woman (2018 est.) Country comparison to the world: 91st\n\n===Population growth rate===\n:0.97% (2018 est.) Country comparison to the world: 114th\n\n===Contraceptive prevalence rate===\n:54.6% (2016)\n\n===Net migration rate===\n:-0.9 migrant(s)/1,000 population (2018 est.) Country comparison to the world: 138th\n\n===[[Dependency ratio]]s===\n:total dependency ratio: 52.5 (2015 est.)\n:youth dependency ratio: 44.8 (2015 est.)\n:elderly dependency ratio: 7.7 (2015 est.)\n:[[potential support ratio]]: 12.9 (2015 est.)\n\n===Urbanization===\n:urban population: 66.4% of total population (2018)\n:rate of urbanization: 1.97% annual rate of change (2015-20 est.)\n\n===Life expectancy at birth===\n:total population: 64.1 years \n:male: 62.7 years \n:female: 65.6 years (2018 est.)\n\n===Languages===\n:isiZulu (official) 24.7%, isiXhosa (official) 15.6%, Afrikaans (official) 12.1%, Sepedi (official) 9.8%, Setswana (official) 8.9%, English (official) 8.4%, Sesotho (official) 8%, Xitsonga (official) 4%, siSwati (official) 2.6%, Tshivenda (official) 2.5%, isiNdebele (official) 1.6%, other (includes Khoi, Nama, and San languages) 1.9% (2017 est.)\n:note: data represent language spoken most often at home\n\n===Education expenditures===\n:6.1% of GDP (2017) Country comparison to the world: 34th\n\n===Literacy===\ndefinition: age 15 and over can read and write (2015 est.)\n:total population: 94.4% \n:male: 95.4% \n:female: 93.4% (2015 est.)\n\n===School life expectancy (primary to tertiary education)===\n:total: 14 years \n:male: 13 years \n:female: 14 years (2016)\n\n===Unemployment, youth ages 15-24===\n:total: 53.5% \n:male: 49.3% \n:female: 58.7% (2017 est.)\n\n==Immigration==\n[[File:COB data South Africa.PNG|right|thumb]]\n{{main article|Immigration to South Africa}}\nSouth Africa hosts a sizeable refugee and asylum seeker population. According to the ''World Refugee Survey 2008'', published by the U.S. Committee for Refugees and Immigrants, this population numbered approximately 144,700 in 2007.<ref name=\"World Refugee Survey 2008\"/> Groups of refugees and asylum seekers numbering over 10,000 included people from [[Zimbabwe]] (48,400), the [[Democratic Republic of the Congo]] (24,800), and [[Somalia]] (12,900).<ref name=\"World Refugee Survey 2008\"/> These populations mainly lived in Johannesburg, Pretoria, Durban, Cape Town, and Port Elizabeth.<ref name=\"World Refugee Survey 2008\">{{cite news|title=World Refugee Survey 2008|publisher=U.S. Committee for Refugees and Immigrants|date=19 June 2008|url=http://www.refugees.org/survey|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071005040657/http://www.refugees.org/article.aspx?id=1941|archivedate=5 October 2007|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Many refugees have now also started to work and live in rural areas in provinces such as [[Mpumalanga]] and [[KwaZulu-Natal]].\n\nStatistics SA assumes in some of their calculations that there are fewer than 2 million immigrants in South Africa.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.statssa.gov.za/PublicationsHTML/P03022009/html/P03022009_6.html |archive-url=https://archive.today/20120805230305/http://www.statssa.gov.za/PublicationsHTML/P03022009/html/P03022009_6.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=5 August 2012|title=P03022009_6 |publisher=Statssa.gov.za |accessdate=5 January 2014}}</ref> Other institutions, like the police and [[M\u00e9decins Sans Fronti\u00e8res]] place estimate the figure at 4 million.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/africa/4416820.stm So where are Zimbabweans going?], [[BBC News]]. 8 November 2005.</ref><ref>[https://archive.today/20110715230442/http://www.sake24.com/articles/default/display_article.aspx?Channel=News_Home&ArticleId=6-1607_2524944&IsColumnistStory=False SA population may be much larger than previously thought] [[Beeld]] 1 June 2009.</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.home-affairs.gov.za/faq.asp |title=Archived copy |accessdate=6 February 2016|url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100918042227/http://www.home-affairs.gov.za/faq.asp |archivedate=18 September 2010 |df=dmy-all }} </ref><ref>[[South African Police Service]] [http://www.saps.gov.za/saps_profile/strategic_framework/annual_report/2008_2009/2_crime_situation_sa.pdf 2009 Annual Report] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130725220235/http://www.saps.gov.za/saps_profile/strategic_framework/annual_report/2008_2009/2_crime_situation_sa.pdf |date=25 July 2013 }} page 9 indicating the number exceeds 3 million</ref><ref>[http://www.msf.org.za/viewnews.php?n=308 ]{{dead link|date=January 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Immigration figures===\nImmigration assumptions by Statistics South Africa to South Africa based on race.  Negative numbers represent net migration from South Africa to other countries.<ref name=\"STATSmigration2014\">{{cite web | url=http://www.statssa.gov.za/publications/P0302/P03022014.pdf | title=Mid-year population estimates 2014 | publisher=Statistics South Africa | date=31 July 2014 | accessdate=8 December 2015}}</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! style=\"width:80px;\"|Year\n! style=\"width:80pt;\"|African\n! style=\"width:80px;\"|Asian\n! style=\"width:80px;\"|White\n|- style=\"text-align:right;\" \n|| 1985-2000\n|| 1 135 275\n|| 14 476\n|| -304 112\n|- style=\"text-align:right;\" \n|| 2001-2005\n|| 769 038\n|| 23 335 \n|| -133 782\n|- style=\"text-align:right;\" \n||2006-2010\n|| 922 885 \n|| 34 688\n|| -112 046\n|- style=\"text-align:right;\" \n|| 2011-2015\n|| 1 067 936\n|| 40 929 \n|| -95 158\n|}\n\n==Urbanization==\n\"Urban areas contain about two-thirds of the population; many of these consist of huge informal or [[Shanty town|squatter settlements]].\"<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.britannica.com/place/South-Africa/Languages |accessdate= 25 October 2017 |work= Britannica.com |title= South Africa: Settlement Patterns }}</ref>\n\n===Largest municipalities===\n{{see also|Metropolitan municipality (South Africa)}}\n{{Largest cities of South Africa}}\n\n==Graphs and maps==\n<gallery>\nFile:South Africa Population Pyramid 2011 estimates.png|Population pyramid by population group, 2011\nFile:South Africa 2011 Black African population proportion map.svg|Black population\nFile:South Africa 2011 White population proportion map.svg|White population\nFile:South Africa 2011 Coloured population proportion map.svg|Coloured population\n</gallery>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Statistics South Africa]]\n* [[South African National Census of 2001]]\n* [[South African National Census of 2011]]\n* [[Afrikaans speaking population in South Africa]]\n* [[Jewish population of South Africa]]\n* [[Ethnic groups in South Africa by municipality]]\n\n==References==\n\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*{{cite web|last=Alexander|first=Mary|title=Black, white \u2013 or South African?|url=http://www.southafrica.info:80/ess_info/sa_glance/constitution/identity-300606.htm|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060704213525/http://www.southafrica.info/ess_info/sa_glance/constitution/identity-300606.htm|url-status=dead|archive-date=4 July 2006|date=30 June 2006|publisher=SAinfo|accessdate=26 June 2013|df=dmy-all}}\n*{{cite web|title=A Nation in the Making: A Discussion Document on Macro-Social Trends in South Africa |url=http://www.info.gov.za/otherdocs/2006/socioreport.pdf |year=2006 |publisher=Government of South Africa |accessdate=26 June 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060711171013/http://www.info.gov.za/otherdocs/2006/socioreport.pdf |archivedate=11 July 2006 |df=dmy }}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Demographics of South Africa}}\n{{Wikiquote|South Africans}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20160206124827/http://www.sundaystandard.info/zimbabwean-refugees-suffer-botswana-and-south-africa Sunday Standard article on Zimbabwe Refugee Crisis]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20160206124826/http://www.statssa.gov.za/publications/Report-03-03-01/Report-03-03-01.pdf Contains information on the South African middle class]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20150930160435/http://www.mistra.org.za/Library/ConferencePaper/Documents/Middle%20Class%20in%20South%20Africa-Significance,%20role%20and%20impact.pdf Middle Class in South Africa-Significance, role and impact]\n\n{{Demographics of South Africa}}\n{{Ethnic groups in South Africa}}\n{{South Africa topics}}\n{{Africa in topic|Demographics of}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Demographics of South Africa, Republic of}}\n[[Category:Demographics of South Africa| ]]\n", "name_user": "Eduardm", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eCensuses:Addressed North West and Northern Province disambiguation", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Demographics_of_South_Africa"}
{"title_page": "Christian Rapp (author)", "text_new": "{{short description|Austrian author, cultural scientist, and exhibition curator}}\n{{Multiple issues|\n{{Orphan|date=June 2018}}\n{{more citations needed|date=June 2018}}\n}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2019}}\n\n''' Christian Rapp''' (born 1964 in Vienna) is an Austrian author, cultural scientist and exhibition curator.\n\n== Life ==\nChristian Rapp studied [[Theater Studies|theater]], [[Media studies|media]], and [[art history]] at the [[University of Vienna]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.schallaburg.at/de/presse/presse-vorschau-2014-jubel-elend.-leben-mit-dem-grossen-krieg-1914-1918/03medieninformation-team_final.pdf |title=Christian Rapp |access-date=10 June 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140503153118/http://www.schallaburg.at/de/presse/presse-vorschau-2014-jubel-elend.-leben-mit-dem-grossen-krieg-1914-1918/03medieninformation-team_final.pdf |archive-date=3 May 2014 |url-status=dead }} in einer Presseinformation der Schallaburg</ref> From 1988 to 1990 he was cultural editor of the \"AZ\" and the courier. Christian Rapp has been working as an exhibition curator since 1990, focusing on urban history, contemporary history, traffic and tourism history. He curated exhibitions for the Technical Museum Vienna, the [[Vienna Museum]], the [[Jewish Museum Vienna]], the Lower Austrian Provincial Exhibition and others. In 1995 he was with the work '' H\u00f6henrausch. The German mountain film '' zum Dr. phil. PhD. Since 2002 he is a lecturer at the Institute for European Ethnology of the University of Vienna. From 2004 to 2008 he was a lecturer in the postgraduate course \"ECM-Exhibition and Cultural Communication Management\" of the [[University of Applied Arts Vienna]].\nOn 1 January 2018 he followed Stefan Karner as scientific director in the History of [[Lower Austria]] and  '' Rapp becomes new leader in the House of History ''.\n\n== Publications ==\n* ''H\u00f6henrausch. Der deutsche Bergfilm.'' Sonderzahl, Wien um 1997, {{ISBN|3-85449-108-5}}.\n* with Ulrike Felber, [[Elke Krasny]]: ''Smart Exports. \u00d6sterreich auf den Weltausstellungen 1851\u20132000.'' Brandst\u00e4tter, Wien 2000, {{ISBN|3-85498-068-X}}.\n* with Wolfgang Kos: ''Alt-Wien: die Stadt, die niemals war.'' Czernin, Wien 2004, {{ISBN|3-7076-0193-5}}.\n* with Nadia Rapp-Wimberger: ''Arbeite, Sammle, Vermehre. Von der ersten Oesterreichischen Spar-Casse zur Erste Bank.'' Brandst\u00e4tter, Wien 2005, {{ISBN|3-85498-404-9}}.\n* ''Spurwechsel. Wien lernt Auto fahren.'' Brandst\u00e4tter, Wien 2006, {{ISBN|3-902510-84-6}} (Ausstellungskatalog: Technisches Museum, Wien, 12. Oktober 2006 \u2013 28. Februar 2007)\n* with Elke Doppler, S\u00e1ndor B\u00e9k\u00e9si (Hrsg.): ''Am Puls der Stadt. 2000 Jahre Karlsplatz.'' Czernin, Wien 2008, {{ISBN|978-3-7076-0279-1}}.\n* with Matthias Beitl, Nadia Rapp-Wimberger (Hrsg.): ''Wer hat, der hat. Eine illustrierte Geschichte des Sparens.'' Metro, Wien 2009, {{ISBN|978-3-902517-96-8}}.\n* with Markus Kristan: ''Worauf freut sich der Wiener wenn er vom Urlaub kommt? Ankerbrot. Die Geschichte einer gro\u00dfen B\u00e4ckerei.'' Brandst\u00e4tter, Wien 2011, {{ISBN|978-3-85033-555-3}}.\n* with Nadia Rapp-Wimberger: ''Bad Ischl \u2013 Mit und ohne Kaiser.'' Brandst\u00e4tter, Wien 2016, {{ISBN|978-3-85033-991-9}}.\n\n== Exhibitions ==\n* with [[Elke Krasny]], Nadia Rapp-Wimberger: ''Von Samoa zum Isonzo. Die Fotografin und Reisejournalistin Alice Schalek.'' J\u00fcdisches Museum Wien, 1999.\n* with Gertraud Liesenfeld, Klara L\u00f6ffler, Michael Weese: ''Nichtstun. Vom Flanieren, Pausieren, Blaumachen und M\u00fcssiggehen.'' [[\u00d6sterreichisches Museum f\u00fcr Volkskunde]] Wien, 2000.\n* with Wolfgang Kos: ''Alt Wien. Die Stadt, die niemals war.'' Wien Museum 2004.\n* ''Spurwechsel \u2013 Wien lernt Autofahren.'' Technisches Museum Wien 2005.\n* with Nadia Rapp-Wimberger: ''\u00d6sterreichische Riviera \u2013 Wien entdeckt das Meer.'' Wien Museum 2013.\n* with Peter Fritz u.&nbsp;a.: ''Jubel und Elend \u2013 Leben mit dem Gro\u00dfen Krieg 1914\u20131918.'' [[Schallaburg]] 2014.\n* Verkehrsmuseum Remise 2014\n\n== Footnotes ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{DNB-Portal|1045515698|NAME=Christian Rapp}}\n* [http://search.obvsg.at/primo_library/libweb/action/search.do?dscnt=0&vl(drEndMonth5)=00&scp.scps=scope%3A%28%22ONB%22%29&vl(1UI2)=contains&tab=default_tab&dstmp=1399108364141&srt=rank&vl(drStartMonth5)=00&mode=Advanced&vl(45332779UI1)=title&vl(1UIStartWith1)=contains&vl(413992940UI2)=any&tb=t&indx=1&vl(drStartYear5)=Jahr&vl(freeText0)=Rapp%20%2C%20%20Christian&fn=search&vid=ONB&vl(freeText2)=&vl(45332932UI0)=creator&vl(drStartDay5)=00&vl(45333860UI4)=all_items&title2=2&frbg=&ct=search&vl(45740927UI3)=all_items&dum=true&vl(drEndDay5)=00&vl(1UIStartWith0)=exact&Submit=Suche&vl(drEndYear5)=Jahr&vl(freeText1)= Literatur von Christian Rapp im Katalog der \u00d6sterreichischen Nationalbibliothek]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Rapp, Christian}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1964 births]]\n[[Category:Austrian male writers]]\n\n\n{{Austria-writer-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Austrian author, cultural scientist, and exhibition curator}}\n{{Multiple issues|\n{{Orphan|date=June 2018}}\n{{BLP sources|date=April 2020}}\n}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2019}}\n\n''' Christian Rapp''' (born 1964 in Vienna) is an Austrian author, cultural scientist and exhibition curator.\n\n== Life ==\nChristian Rapp studied [[Theater Studies|theater]], [[Media studies|media]], and [[art history]] at the [[University of Vienna]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.schallaburg.at/de/presse/presse-vorschau-2014-jubel-elend.-leben-mit-dem-grossen-krieg-1914-1918/03medieninformation-team_final.pdf |title=Christian Rapp |access-date=10 June 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140503153118/http://www.schallaburg.at/de/presse/presse-vorschau-2014-jubel-elend.-leben-mit-dem-grossen-krieg-1914-1918/03medieninformation-team_final.pdf |archive-date=3 May 2014 |url-status=dead }} in einer Presseinformation der Schallaburg</ref> From 1988 to 1990 he was cultural editor of the \"AZ\" and the courier. Christian Rapp has been working as an exhibition curator since 1990, focusing on urban history, contemporary history, traffic and tourism history. He curated exhibitions for the Technical Museum Vienna, the [[Vienna Museum]], the [[Jewish Museum Vienna]], the Lower Austrian Provincial Exhibition and others. In 1995 he was with the work '' H\u00f6henrausch. The German mountain film '' zum Dr. phil. PhD. Since 2002 he is a lecturer at the Institute for European Ethnology of the University of Vienna. From 2004 to 2008 he was a lecturer in the postgraduate course \"ECM-Exhibition and Cultural Communication Management\" of the [[University of Applied Arts Vienna]].\nOn 1 January 2018 he followed Stefan Karner as scientific director in the History of [[Lower Austria]] and  '' Rapp becomes new leader in the House of History ''.\n\n== Publications ==\n* ''H\u00f6henrausch. Der deutsche Bergfilm.'' Sonderzahl, Wien um 1997, {{ISBN|3-85449-108-5}}.\n* with Ulrike Felber, [[Elke Krasny]]: ''Smart Exports. \u00d6sterreich auf den Weltausstellungen 1851\u20132000.'' Brandst\u00e4tter, Wien 2000, {{ISBN|3-85498-068-X}}.\n* with Wolfgang Kos: ''Alt-Wien: die Stadt, die niemals war.'' Czernin, Wien 2004, {{ISBN|3-7076-0193-5}}.\n* with Nadia Rapp-Wimberger: ''Arbeite, Sammle, Vermehre. Von der ersten Oesterreichischen Spar-Casse zur Erste Bank.'' Brandst\u00e4tter, Wien 2005, {{ISBN|3-85498-404-9}}.\n* ''Spurwechsel. Wien lernt Auto fahren.'' Brandst\u00e4tter, Wien 2006, {{ISBN|3-902510-84-6}} (Ausstellungskatalog: Technisches Museum, Wien, 12. Oktober 2006 \u2013 28. Februar 2007)\n* with Elke Doppler, S\u00e1ndor B\u00e9k\u00e9si (Hrsg.): ''Am Puls der Stadt. 2000 Jahre Karlsplatz.'' Czernin, Wien 2008, {{ISBN|978-3-7076-0279-1}}.\n* with Matthias Beitl, Nadia Rapp-Wimberger (Hrsg.): ''Wer hat, der hat. Eine illustrierte Geschichte des Sparens.'' Metro, Wien 2009, {{ISBN|978-3-902517-96-8}}.\n* with Markus Kristan: ''Worauf freut sich der Wiener wenn er vom Urlaub kommt? Ankerbrot. Die Geschichte einer gro\u00dfen B\u00e4ckerei.'' Brandst\u00e4tter, Wien 2011, {{ISBN|978-3-85033-555-3}}.\n* with Nadia Rapp-Wimberger: ''Bad Ischl \u2013 Mit und ohne Kaiser.'' Brandst\u00e4tter, Wien 2016, {{ISBN|978-3-85033-991-9}}.\n\n== Exhibitions ==\n* with [[Elke Krasny]], Nadia Rapp-Wimberger: ''Von Samoa zum Isonzo. Die Fotografin und Reisejournalistin Alice Schalek.'' J\u00fcdisches Museum Wien, 1999.\n* with Gertraud Liesenfeld, Klara L\u00f6ffler, Michael Weese: ''Nichtstun. Vom Flanieren, Pausieren, Blaumachen und M\u00fcssiggehen.'' [[\u00d6sterreichisches Museum f\u00fcr Volkskunde]] Wien, 2000.\n* with Wolfgang Kos: ''Alt Wien. Die Stadt, die niemals war.'' Wien Museum 2004.\n* ''Spurwechsel \u2013 Wien lernt Autofahren.'' Technisches Museum Wien 2005.\n* with Nadia Rapp-Wimberger: ''\u00d6sterreichische Riviera \u2013 Wien entdeckt das Meer.'' Wien Museum 2013.\n* with Peter Fritz u.&nbsp;a.: ''Jubel und Elend \u2013 Leben mit dem Gro\u00dfen Krieg 1914\u20131918.'' [[Schallaburg]] 2014.\n* Verkehrsmuseum Remise 2014\n\n== Footnotes ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{DNB-Portal|1045515698|NAME=Christian Rapp}}\n* [http://search.obvsg.at/primo_library/libweb/action/search.do?dscnt=0&vl(drEndMonth5)=00&scp.scps=scope%3A%28%22ONB%22%29&vl(1UI2)=contains&tab=default_tab&dstmp=1399108364141&srt=rank&vl(drStartMonth5)=00&mode=Advanced&vl(45332779UI1)=title&vl(1UIStartWith1)=contains&vl(413992940UI2)=any&tb=t&indx=1&vl(drStartYear5)=Jahr&vl(freeText0)=Rapp%20%2C%20%20Christian&fn=search&vid=ONB&vl(freeText2)=&vl(45332932UI0)=creator&vl(drStartDay5)=00&vl(45333860UI4)=all_items&title2=2&frbg=&ct=search&vl(45740927UI3)=all_items&dum=true&vl(drEndDay5)=00&vl(1UIStartWith0)=exact&Submit=Suche&vl(drEndYear5)=Jahr&vl(freeText1)= Literatur von Christian Rapp im Katalog der \u00d6sterreichischen Nationalbibliothek]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Rapp, Christian}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1964 births]]\n[[Category:Austrian male writers]]\n\n\n{{Austria-writer-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Johnsoniensis", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eExternal links:eLinks)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Christian_Rapp_(author)"}
{"title_page": "Celtic Woman", "text_new": "{{short description|All-female Irish musical ensemble}}\n{{Unreliable sources|date=December 2019}}\n{{EngvarB|date=August 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2020}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name             = Celtic Woman\n| background       = group_or_band\n| image            = Celtic Woman performs at Macquarie Shopping Centre, Sydney (cropped).jpg\n| landscape        = yes\n| caption          = From left to right: Lisa Lambe, Susan McFadden, Chloe Agnew, and Mairead Nesbitt (August 2012)\n| origin           = Ireland\n| genre            = {{flatlist|\n*[[Celtic music|Celtic]]\n*[[Folk music|folk]]\n*[[new-age music]]\n*[[Adult contemporary music|adult contemporary]]/pop\n*[[Classical crossover (musical genre)|classical crossover]]\n}}\n| years_active     = 2004\u2013present\n| label            = [[Manhattan Records|Manhattan]]\n| website          = [http://www.CelticWoman.com/ CelticWoman.com]\n| current_members  = [[Chlo\u00eb Agnew]]<br />[[M\u00e1ir\u00e9ad Carlin]]<br />[[Tara McNeill]]<br />[[Megan Walsh]]\n| past_members     = [[\u00d3rla Fallon]]<br />[[Lynn Hilary]]<br />[[Lisa Kelly]]<br />[[Lisa Lambe]]<br />[[Susan McFadden]]<br />[[Eabha McMahon]]<br />[[M\u00e1ir\u00e9ad Nesbitt]]<br />[[M\u00e9av N\u00ed Mhaolchatha]]<br />[[Deirdre Shannon]]<br  />[[Alex Sharpe]]<br />[[Hayley Westenra]]<br />\n}}\n\n'''Celtic Woman''' is an all-female Irish musical ensemble conceived and created by David Kavanagh, Sharon Browne<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.boston.com/news/globe/living/articles/2005/07/24/swept_away_by_the_sounds_of_irelands_celtic_woman/ |title=Swept away by the sounds of Ireland's 'Celtic Woman' |date=24 July 2005 |accessdate=22 May 2010 |work=Boston Globe |first=Steve |last=Morse}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.independent.ie/lifestyle/well-take-manhattan-2114828.html |title=We'll Take Manhattan |work=The Irish Independent  |date=10 March 2010 |accessdate=27 May 2010 |first=Donal |last=Lynch}}</ref> and [[David Downes (Irish composer)|David Downes]], a former musical director of the Irish stage show ''[[Riverdance]].''<ref>{{cite web |url=http://jksalescompany.com/dw/CelticWoman.html |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080930145822/http://www.jksalescompany.com/dw/CelticWoman.html |archivedate=30 September 2008 |title=Celtic Woman}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.christmastwist.com/2007_09_01_archive.html |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081201135543/http://www.christmastwist.com/2007_09_01_archive.html |archivedate=1 December 2008 |title=Now That's What I Call Christmas, Vol. 3}}</ref> In 2004, Downes recruited five Irish female musicians who had not previously performed together: vocalists [[Chlo\u00eb Agnew]], [[\u00d3rla Fallon]], [[Lisa Kelly]] and [[M\u00e9av N\u00ed Mhaolchatha]], and fiddler [[M\u00e1ir\u00e9ad Nesbitt]], and shaped them into the first lineup of the group that he named \"Celtic Woman\", a specialty group. Downes chose a repertoire that ranged from traditional [[Celtic music|Celtic tunes]] to modern songs.\n\nThe show was meant to be a one-time event held in [[Dublin]], Ireland, but multiple airings on [[PBS]] helped boost the group's popularity.\n\nThe group's line-up has changed over the years. Eleven albums have been released under the name \"Celtic Woman\": ''[[Celtic Woman (album)|Celtic Woman]]'', ''[[Celtic Woman: A Christmas Celebration]]'', ''[[Celtic Woman: A New Journey]]'', ''[[Celtic Woman: The Greatest Journey]]'', ''[[Celtic Woman: Songs from the Heart]]'', ''[[Celtic Woman: Lullaby]]'', ''[[Celtic Woman: Believe]]'', ''[[Celtic Woman: Home for Christmas]]'', ''[[Celtic Woman: Emerald - Musical Gems]]'', ''[[Celtic Woman: Destiny]]'', ''[[Celtic Woman: Voices of Angels]],'' and ''[[Celtic Woman: Ancient Land]].'' The group has undertaken a number of world tours. Cumulatively, albums by Celtic Woman have sold over nine million records worldwide.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.irishecho.com.au/2010/06/30/celtic-woman-taking-the-irish-music-world-by-storm/4023 |title=Celtic Woman taking the Irish music world by storm &#124; Australia's Irish Website |newspaper=[[Irish Echo]] |accessdate=10 March 2016 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160309103242/http://www.irishecho.com.au/2010/06/30/celtic-woman-taking-the-irish-music-world-by-storm/4023 |archivedate= 9 March 2016 }}</ref>\n\nThe foundation for Celtic music's popularity outside Ireland and Europe was built by tapping into the success of artists such as [[Enya]], [[Moya Brennan]] and [[Clannad (musical group)|Clannad]], along with stage shows ''[[Riverdance]]'' and ''[[Lord of the Dance (musical)|Lord of the Dance]].'' Celtic Woman has been described as being \"''Riverdance'' for the voice.\"<ref name=\"riverdancevoice\">{{cite news |url=http://www.deirdreshannon.com/IrelandOnSunday_050206.htm |title=''Celtic Woman'' in Dublin |work=Ireland on Sunday |first=Danny |last=McElhinney |date=5 February 2006 |accessdate=13 February 2007 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070907031308/http://www.deirdreshannon.com/IrelandOnSunday_050206.htm |archivedate=7 September 2007}}</ref>\n\nCeltic Woman has been named [[Billboard charts|Billboard]] [[World music|World Album]] Artist of the Year six times.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/charts/year-end|title=Charts \u2013 Year End|website=Billboard|access-date=2 May 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.broadwayworld.com/orlando/article/Celtic-Woman-to-Perform-at-Bob-Carr-Theater-1031-20150916|title=Celtic Woman to Perform at Bob Carr Theater, 10/31|last=Desk|first=BWW News|website=BroadwayWorld.com|access-date=2 May 2016}}</ref>\n\n== Tours ==\nCeltic Woman has performed numerous tours in North America, with additional ones overseas. The group appeared live in more than a dozen US cities in 2005 for their original album debut, [[Celtic Woman The Show]].<ref name=\"dualtour\">{{cite web|url=http://www.livedaily.com/news/9048.html |title=Celtic Woman members get along harmoniously |work=LiveDaily.com |accessdate=29 May 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080917210058/http://www.livedaily.com/news/9048.html |archivedate=17 September 2008 }}</ref> This was followed by all five members' solo albums recorded between 2000 and 2004 being released in the US on 10 January 2006.\n\nThe group toured the United States twice with their [[Celtic Woman: A New Journey|A New Journey]] tour, visiting 88 cities in 2007 and over 75 cities in 2008. In early April 2008 it was announced that [[The High Kings]] would be opening the act for the group through June 2008.<ref name=\"highkings\">{{cite web |url=http://CelticWoman.com/ |title=Celtic Woman Home Page |work=CelticWoman.com |accessdate=29 May 2008}}</ref> The tour began on 14 February 2007 in Tampa with initial dates announced through 29 June 2007. New dates for Europe running 22 September 22 to 9 October 2007 were announced in May 2007 along with fall North American dates running 10 October to 17 November 2007 and some Japan dates. The tour finished on 6 October 2008 in Amsterdam.\n\nThe 2009 Isle of Hope was announced in late 2008, and features a blend of original music from composer David Downes and Brendan Graham (the author of the group favourite \"[[You Raise Me Up]]\"), renditions of songs such as \"Fields of Gold\" and \"Have I Told You Lately That I Love You\" and traditional performances of \"[[Danny Boy]]\", \"The Sky and the Dawn and the Sun\" and \"[[Spanish Lady]]\". This tour finished on 22 November 2009.\n\nThe 2010\u201311 tour called [[Celtic Woman: Songs from the Heart|Songs from the Heart]], featured some of the same music and some new music. The tour featured [[Chlo\u00eb Agnew]], [[Lisa Kelly]], [[Lynn Hilary]], [[Alex Sharpe]], and [[M\u00e1ir\u00e9ad Nesbitt]]. It began in February 2010.<ref name=\"cc091114\">{{cite news|url=http://www.californiachronicle.com/articles/yb/137741350 |title=PBS helps lift group Celtic Woman to U.S. popularity |work=El Paso Times via California Chronicle |first=Doug |last=Pullen |date=14 November 2009 |accessdate=25 November 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120227041729/http://www.californiachronicle.com/articles/yb/137741350 |archivedate=27 February 2012 }}</ref><ref name=\"tds0911\">{{cite news |url=http://www.mydesert.com/article/20091119/LIFESTYLES0101/911180374/1026/news12 |archive-url=https://archive.today/20091126042816/http://www.mydesert.com/article/20091119/LIFESTYLES0101/911180374/1026/news12 |url-status=dead |archive-date=26 November 2009 |title=Singer has even higher hopes |work=The Desert Sun |first=Judith |last=Salkin |date=19 November 2009 |accessdate=25 November 2009}}</ref>\n\nA second \"Songs from the Heart\" tour opened in February 2011 with Agnew, Kelly, new member [[Lisa Lambe]], and Nesbitt and consisted of about 80 concerts in North America in spring 2011<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.CelticWoman.com/tour-dates/ |title=Songs from the Heart Tour dates for North America |accessdate=12 January 2011}}</ref> and 10 performances in Germany and Austria during summer 2011.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.CelticWoman.com/german-tour-dates/ |title=Songs from the Heart Tour dates for Europe |accessdate=12 January 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101223192249/http://www.celticwoman.com/german-tour-dates/ |archivedate=23 December 2010 }}</ref>\n\nThe Symphony Tour featuring songs from their Christmas Album ''A Christmas Celebration'' took place during December 2011.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.CelticWoman.com/symphony-tour-dates/ |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130117022114/http://www.celticwoman.com/symphony-tour-dates/ |archivedate=17 January 2013 |title=Symphony Tour Dates 2012 |url-status=dead  }}</ref>\n\nThe [[Celtic Woman: Believe|Believe]] 2012 North American Tour ran between February 2012 and April 2012.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.CelticWoman.com/north-american-tour-dates-2012/ |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130530135954/http://www.celticwoman.com/north-american-tour-dates-2012/ |archivedate=30 May 2013 |title=North American Tour Dates 2012 |url-status=dead  }}</ref> Following directly onto this, the BELIEVE European tour took place between May and June 2012.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.CelticWoman.com/eu-tour-dates/ |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130510171405/http://www.celticwoman.com/eu-tour-dates/ |archivedate=10 May 2013 |title=European Tour Dates |url-status=dead  }}</ref> Lisa Kelly, who was expecting her fourth child, did not participate in the 2012 tours,<ref name=\"Celtic Woman\">{{cite web|url=http://www.CelticWoman.com/ |title=Official Website of Irish Music Sensation |publisher=Celtic Woman |accessdate=10 March 2016}}</ref> and was replaced by Susan McFadden,<ref name=\"Celtic Woman\"/> the younger sister of former [[Westlife]] member [[Brian McFadden]].\n\nAnother Symphony Tour was announced for the 2012 Christmas season, featuring Agnew, Lambe, Nesbitt and McFadden.  The tour began on 1 December and continued on till 22 December.\n\nCeltic Woman took \"Believe\" on tour again from February to June 2013, with the same line-up.  On 15 January 2013, Lisa Kelly announced her intentions to open \"The Lisa Kelly Voice Academy\", located in Peachtree City, GA, and confirmed that she would not be returning to Celtic Woman.  Her husband, Scott Porter, also announced his departure as CEO of Celtic Woman.\n\nCeltic Woman took \"Believe\" to Europe in October 2013 and visited the US on their Symphony Tour in December 2013. The Australian Tour for \"Believe\", previously scheduled for September 2013, was rescheduled to January 2014.\n\nCeltic Woman toured in the US from February to June 2014 on their Emerald Tour to celebrate the heritage of the Emerald Isles and to promote their new album called Celtic Woman: Emerald Musical Gems. [[Lynn Hilary]] came back for the Emerald Tour as [[Lisa Lambe]] left in mid-March for a role in the play ''Breaking Dad,'' Ross O'Carroll-Kelly's sequel to ''Between Foxrock and a Hard Place,'' in which Lisa had played Sorcha.  ''Breaking Dad,'' ran from 25 April to 17 May at the Gaiety Theatre in Dublin, Ireland.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gaietytheatre.ie/index.php/whats-on-buy-tickets/calendar/ross-ocarroll-kelly-breaking-dad/528 |title=The Gaiety Theatre \u2013 Irish Theatre in Dublin |website=Gaietytheatre.ie |accessdate=10 March 2016}}</ref> As well as the US, Celtic Woman visited Brazil, the UK, and Europe in Autumn 2014 on their Emerald Tour \u2013 making their debut in Brazil and the UK.\n\nCeltic Woman toured the US for their \"Symphony Tour\" in December 2014 and again for the Decade 10th Anniversary  Tour in March 2015 to celebrate the group's 10th anniversary. Their November 2014 Emerald European Tour was rescheduled to February 2015 and became part of the Decade 10th Anniversary  Tour instead.\n\nThey visited Australia for the Decade 10th Anniversary Tour in September 2015 for the first time since January 2014, and returned to the UK in November 2015.{{update after|2015|11|1}}\n\nThe [[Destiny (Celtic Woman album)|Destiny]] world tour was from 4 March \u2013 29 October 2016.\n\nThe [[Celtic Woman: Voices of Angels|Voices of Angels]] world tour was from 2 March \u2013 2 November 2017.\n\nOn 6 October 2017, Celtic Woman officially announced their 2018 tour, the ''Homecoming World Tour''. The North American leg of the Homecoming tour ran from 1 March 2018 \u2013 17 June 2018.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.celticwoman.com/news/2018-homecoming-tour-dates-announced/|title=2018 Homecoming Tour Dates Announced|website=celticwoman.com|access-date=14 January 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.celticwoman.com/tour-dates|title=Tour|website=celticwoman.com|access-date=14 January 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn 31 July 2018, the group announced ''The Best of Christmas'' tour, which ran from 26 November \u2013 22 December 2018.\n\nOn 17 October 2018, the group announced The [[Celtic Woman: Ancient Land|Ancient Land]] tour,  which ran from 28 February 2019 -  18 November 2019.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.broadwayworld.com/bwwmusic/article/Grammy-Nominated-Celtic-Woman-Announce-New-Tour-Ancient-Land-20181017|title=Grammy Nominated Celtic Woman Announce New Tour 'Ancient Land'|website=BroadwayWorld}}</ref>\n\nOn 4 October 2019, the Celebration 15th Anniversary tour was announced to run from 27 February 2020 \u2013 7 June 2020 to celebrate the group's 15th Anniversary, but was cut short in March due to the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|corona virus pandemic.]] An announcement was made that the cancelled dates would be rescheduled. On 20 March 2020, the rescheduled Celebration 15th Anniversary tour was announced to run from 25 February 2021 \u2013  4 June 2021 and more tour dates would be announced soon.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.celticwoman.com/tour-rescheduling-announcement-2020/|title=TOUR RESCHEDULING ANNOUNCEMENT|last=|first=|date=|website=www.celticwoman.com|publisher=Celtic Woman|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-14}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.celticwoman.com/news/celebration-tour-rescheduled-/|title=CELEBRATION TOUR RESCHEDULED|date=20 March 2020|website=Celtic Woman|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n===Tours 2004 \u2013 2021===\n#[[Celtic Woman (album)|Celtic Woman]] (2004)\n#[[Celtic Woman The Show]] (2005\u20132006)\n#[[Celtic Woman: A Christmas Celebration]] (2006)\n#[[Celtic Woman: A New Journey]] (2006\u20132008)\n#Celtic Woman: Isle of Hope (2009)\n#[[Celtic Woman: Songs from the Heart]] (2009\u20132011)\n#Celtic Woman: The Symphony Tour (Christmas 2011\u20132014)\n#[[Celtic Woman: Believe]] (2012\u20132014)\n#[[Celtic Woman: Home for Christmas]] (2012)\n#[[Celtic Woman: Emerald - Musical Gems]] (2013\u20132014)\n#Celtic Woman: Decade 10th Anniversary (2014\u20132015)\n#[[Celtic Woman: Destiny]] (2016)\n#[[Celtic Woman: Voices of Angels]] (2017)\n#[[Celtic Woman: Homecoming Live from Ireland|Celtic Woman: Homecoming \u2013 Live from Ireland]] (2018)\n#[[Celtic Woman: Ancient Land]] (2018\u20132019)\n#Celtic Woman: Celebration 15th Anniversary (2020\u20132021)\n\n== Albums ==\nCeltic Woman was taped on 15 September 2004 for [[PBS]] television at [[The Helix (Dublin)|The Helix]] in Dublin in front of a sold-out audience. Organized by producer Sharon Browne, Chairman & CEO Dave Kavanagh, television producer and director Avril MacRory, and musical director and composer [[David Downes (Irish composer)|David Downes]], this performance was first broadcast on PBS during March 2005 in the United States. Within weeks the group's eponymous debut album, ''Celtic Woman'', reached No. 1 on ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]''<nowiki>'s</nowiki> World Music chart, eventually breaking [[Andrea Bocelli]]'s long-standing record of chart-topping longevity on 22 July 2006 by having stayed at No. 1 for 68 weeks.<ref name=\"CW213\">{{cite web |url=http://www.CelticWoman.com/viewSection.asp?idSection=213 |title=Celtic Woman enters record books with 68 weeks at No. 1 |work=CelticWoman.com |accessdate=13 February 2007 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070223143919/http://www.celticwoman.com/viewSection.asp?idSection=213 |archivedate=23 February 2007 |url-status=dead  }}</ref> The album held the top position on the ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' World Music chart for 81 weeks total.<ref name=\"CW209\">{{cite web |url=http://www.CelticWoman.com/viewSection.asp?idSection=209 |title=November 06 |work=CelticWoman.com |accessdate=13 February 2007 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070223143719/http://www.celticwoman.com/viewSection.asp?idSection=209 |archivedate=23 February 2007 |url-status=dead  }}</ref> Much of the group's success in America has been credited to the extensive PBS publicity throughout 2005. The live performance at The Helix was released on DVD alongside the studio album.\n\nThe release of the second album, ''[[Celtic Woman: A Christmas Celebration]]'', on 19 October 2006 knocked their first album to the No. 2 spot on the World Music chart.<ref name=\"CW209\"/>\n\nIn preparation for their third studio album, Celtic Woman performed at [[Slane Castle]] in County Meath, Ireland, on 23 and 24 August 2006, with this show airing on PBS during December 2006. The studio album, titled ''[[Celtic Woman: A New Journey]]'', was released on 30 January 2007. As with their debut, the live performance was released on DVD simultaneously. This album immediately hit the [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]] at No. 4<ref name=\"prn\">{{cite press release|url=http://sev.prnewswire.com/entertainment/20070207/NYW12207022007-1.html |title=Celtic Woman Debut at #4... |agency=PR Newswire |date=7 February 2007 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071013163057/http://sev.prnewswire.com/entertainment/20070207/NYW12207022007-1.html |archivedate=13 October 2007 |url-status=dead  }}</ref> and the Billboard World Music chart at No. 1,<ref name=\"bbworld\">{{cite news |url=http://billboard.biz/bbbiz/content_display/industry/e3i0c4f370624146d95dedde46dfadd0400 |title=Better 'Late' Than Never: Jones Debuts At No. 1 |work=Billboard |first=Jonathan |last=Cohen |date=7 February 2007 |accessdate=13 February 2007}}</ref> moving their previous two releases down a notch and securing the top three positions on that chart for the group.\n\nIn response to the popularity of the performance at [[Slane Castle]] in 2006, [[PBS]] aired a special concert of Celtic Woman performing again in [[The Helix (Dublin)|The Helix Theatre]], Dublin, Ireland on 7 December 2007. This performance included songs from the group's second album, ''Celtic Woman: A Christmas Celebration''.\n\nA fourth album, ''[[Celtic Woman: The Greatest Journey]]'', was released on 28 October 2008.\n\nThe group's fifth album, ''[[Celtic Woman: Songs from the Heart]]'', was released 26 January 2010. It peaked at No. 48 in July 2010 on the [[Australian Record Industry Association|ARIA]] Top 50 Albums chart.<ref name=\"aria-sfth\">{{cite web |url=http://www.australian-charts.com/showitem.asp?interpret=Celtic+Woman&titel=Songs+From+The+Heart&cat=a |title=Celtic Woman \u2013 Songs from the Heart (album) |work=Australian-charts.com |date=July 2010 |accessdate=9 July 2010}}</ref> For the album, PBS television presented a special concert starting 28 November 2009. It was taped in HD at Powerscourt House and Gardens in Enniskerry, County Wicklow. It included a 27-member film orchestra, Discovery Gospel choir, 12-member Aontas Choir, 10-member Extreme Rhythm Drummers with an 11-piece bagpipe ensemble.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wvpt.net/CelticWoman2.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091213051716/http://www.wvpt.net/CelticWoman2.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=13 December 2009|title=Songs From the Heart}}</ref>\n\nThe group released their sixth album, ''Lullaby'', available through PBS pledge or the [[QVC]] shopping website.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.CelticWoman.com/details/ |title=Celtic Woman: Lullaby |work=CelticWoman.com |accessdate=21 October 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101018075334/http://www.celticwoman.com/details/ |archivedate=18 October 2010 }}</ref>\nOn 15 February 2011, it was released by other major retailers as a limited edition album. It reached No. 1 on the World Charts and No. 3 on the Children's Charts, a first for Celtic Woman.\n\nThe group filmed a new special on 6 and 7 September 2011 at the [[Fox Theatre (Atlanta, Georgia)|Fox Theater]] in [[Atlanta]], Georgia for PBS broadcast and DVD release. It is titled ''[[Celtic Woman: Believe]]''. The show aired on PBS stations on 3 December 2011. The CD/DVD was released on 24 January 2012.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://atlanta.broadwayworld.com/article/Celtic-Woman-Invites-Fans-To-Exclusive-Filming-Of-New-Live-Concert-in-Sept-20110801 |title=Celtic Woman Invites Fans to Exclusive Filming in Sept. |last=Harrison|first=Joseph|date=1 August 2011|website=BroadwayWorld.com |accessdate=26 August 2011}}</ref>\n\nOn 9 October 2012, the group released its second worldwide Christmas album ''[[Celtic Woman: Home for Christmas|Home for Christmas]]''. This album features the voices of [[Lisa Lambe]], [[Chlo\u00eb Agnew]], [[M\u00e9av N\u00ed Mhaolchatha|Meav Ni Mhaolchatha]], and [[Mairead Nesbitt]] on the fiddle. Another Christmas album, ''[[Celtic Woman: Silent Night]]'' was released on the same day for the United States exclusively.\n\nIn July 2013, Celtic Woman released a promotional video on its YouTube channel for a new PBS special, due to be screened in early 2014. On 24 February 2014, Celtic Woman released a new CD/DVD set and PBS Special, called ''[[Celtic Woman: Emerald - Musical Gems]]''. It features [[Lisa Lambe]], [[Chlo\u00eb Agnew]], [[Mairead Nesbitt]], and [[Susan McFadden]].  The DVD was filmed in April 2013 at a tour stop in [[South Bend, Indiana]] and was aired on PBS, starting in March.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://CelticWoman.com/special-announcement/ |title=Special Announcement |publisher=Celtic Woman |accessdate=10 March 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn 29 May 2015, the group released an album called ''Solo'' featuring ten of the former and current members. On 10 July 2015, the group released an album called ''Decade: The Songs, The Show, The Traditions, The Classics'' featuring all of the former and current members. The albums were released to commemorate the group's 10th Anniversary. \n\nIn August 2015, the group filmed a DVD / TV special and recorded an accompanying album called ''[[Celtic Woman: Destiny]]'', the first for [[M\u00e1ir\u00e9ad Carlin|Mairead Carlin]] and [[\u00c9abha McMahon]]. Nesbitt was the only founding member on the album, although [[Meav Ni Mhaolchatha]] appeared and sang as a guest. Destiny was nominated for [[Grammy Award for Best World Music Album|Best World Music Album]] at the [[59th Annual Grammy Awards]]. This was the first Grammy nomination for the group.\n\nIn August 2016, the group recorded an album called ''[[Celtic Woman: Voices of Angels]]''. The album was the first to feature [[Tara McNeill]] and was also the first album to feature none of the founding members, although [[Meav Ni Mhaolchatha]] again appeared as a guest.\n\nCeltic Woman recorded a live album, ''[[Celtic Woman: Homecoming Live from Ireland|Celtic Woman: Homecoming \u2013 Live from Ireland]]'', at the [[3Arena]] in Dublin on 2 September 2017. The album released in January 2018. It was the first album released by the group to consist entirely of live tracks.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://3arena.ie/artist/celtic-woman1/1869|title=CELTIC WOMAN|website=3Arena|access-date=14 January 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.dublinconcerts.ie/concert/celtic-woman-3arena-september-2nd-2017/|title=Celtic Woman at 3Arena, 2 September 2017|last=(hello@dublinconcerts.ie)|first=Dublin Concerts|website=dublinconcerts.ie|access-date=14 January 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.celticwoman.com/shop/celtic-woman-homecoming-live-from-ireland-dvd-pre-order/|title=Celtic Woman \u2013 Homecoming: Live from Ireland DVD \u2013 PRE-ORDER|last=|first=|date=|website=celticwoman.com|publisher=Celtic Woman|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=14 January 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn 19 July 2018, Celtic Woman announced a new TV special and DVD, to be recorded on 13\u201314 September 2018 at [[Johnstown Castle]] in [[Wexford]], Ireland. This was the group's first outdoor TV special in nine years. The following day, the group announced a studio album to accompany the DVD.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.celticwoman.com/news/first-celtic-woman-outdoor-special-in-9-years-being-filmed-in-johnstown-castle--co--wexford/|title=First Celtic Woman outdoor special in 9 years being filmed in Johnstown Castle, Co. Wexford|last=|first=|date=|website=celticwoman.com|publisher=Celtic Woman|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=17 August 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.celticwoman.com/news/celtic-woman-back-in-recording-studio--/|title=Celtic Woman back in recording studio!|last=|first=|date=|website=celticwoman.com|publisher=Celtic Woman|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=17 August 2018}}</ref> The DVD and album were named ''[[Ancient Land]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.celticwoman.com/news/artwork---tracklist-for-new-celtic-woman-album-revealed/|title=Artwork & Tracklist for New Celtic Woman Album Revealed}}</ref>\n\n''[[The Magic of Christmas (Celtic Woman album)|The Magic of Christmas]]'' is the group's most recent studio album, was released on 25 October 2019 in North America and on 8 November 2019 internationally.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.celticwoman.com/|title=We are delighted to announce our brand new Christmas Album: The Magic Of Christmas|last=|first=|date=|website=celticwoman.com|publisher=Celtic Woman|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=5 October 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn 21 February 2020, Celtic Woman announced their album ''Celebration: 15 years of Music and Magic'' to commemorate the group's 15th Anniversary on Instagram, it was digitally released on 27 February 2020 and the CD was released 27 March 2020.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.instagram.com/p/B81mGCxgqf_/|title=Celtic Woman New Album|last=|first=|date=21 February  2020|website=Instagram|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=21 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.celticwoman.com/news/celtic-woman-is-proud-to-present--celebration---15-years-of-music-and-magic--/|title=Celtic Woman New Album CD Release|last=|first=|date=6 March 2020|website=Celtic Woman|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=6 March 2020}}</ref> \n\n== Members ==\n\n=== Present ===\n<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.CelticWoman.com/meet/|title=Celtic -About|publisher=Celtic Woman|website=CelticWoman.com|access-date=10 February 2017}}</ref>\n\n* '''Chlo\u00eb Agnew''' {{main|Chlo\u00eb Agnew}} Chlo\u00eb Agnew is an Irish singer. She appeared as part of the group at [[The Helix (Dublin)|The Helix]] in Dublin in 2004 as its youngest member. On 5 August 2013, the Celtic Woman website announced that Agnew would be taking a break to focus on solo projects. Her position was filled by Derry-born singer [[M\u00e1ir\u00e9ad Carlin]]. On 22 January 2020, it was announced that Agnew was returning to the group to fill in for McMahon during the ''Celtic Woman Celebration'' spring tour.<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.celticwoman.com/|title=Special Guest Artist Returns|publisher=Celtic Woman|website=www.celticwoman.com|access-date=2020-01-23}}</ref>\n* '''M\u00e1ir\u00e9ad Carlin''' {{main|M\u00e1ir\u00e9ad Carlin}} M\u00e1ir\u00e9ad Carlin is a singer from [[Derry]]. From August 2013, she replaced [[Chlo\u00eb Agnew]], who would be working on solo projects.<ref name=\":5\">{{cite web|url=https://www.celticwoman.com/meet/|title=Meet|website=celticwoman.com}}</ref>\n* '''Tara McNeill''' {{main|Tara McNeill}} Tara McNeill is from [[Antrim, County Antrim|Antrim]].<ref name=\":5\" /> She replaced [[M\u00e1ir\u00e9ad Nesbitt]] in the group's South Africa, South Korea and China ''Destiny'' tour shows in 2016. Her debut album with Celtic Woman was [[Celtic Woman: Voices of Angels]] (2016).\n* '''Megan Walsh'''{{main|Megan Walsh}} Celtic Woman's newest member, replacing Susan McFadden. She was raised in [[Trim, County Meath|Trim]] and [[Navan]]. Walsh debuted with the group in the new studio album and TV special / DVD \"Ancient Land\" recorded in Fall 2018.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.celticwoman.com/news/celtic-woman-welcome-new-member/|title=Celtic Woman welcome new member|publisher=Celtic Woman|website=celticwoman.com|access-date=17 August 2018}}</ref>\n\n=== Former ===\n\n* '''\u00d3rla Fallon''' {{main|\u00d3rla Fallon}} \u00d3rla Fallon is an Irish soloist and singer-songwriter. In 2004, she was invited by composer [[David Downes (Irish composer)|David Downes]] and became one of the founding members of the group. Fallon has performed the harp as well as singing. She was featured in the self-titled debut album ''Celtic Woman,'' ''Celtic Woman: A Christmas Celebration,'' and ''Celtic Woman: A New Journey,'' as well as in the tie-in PBS television specials and DVDs filmed in 2004, 2007, and 2006 respectively. She also toured with the group in 2005 on the inaugural North American, and the ''A New Journey'' tours. In 2009, Fallon announced that she would be leaving the group to spend time with her family, and was replaced by [[Alex Sharpe]].\n* '''Lynn Hilary''' {{main|Lynn Hilary}} Lynn Hilary is an Irish singer, guitarist, and songwriter. In 2007, original member [[M\u00e9av N\u00ed Mhaolchatha]] decided to leave the group to focus on her solo career. Hilary joined the group as N\u00ed Mhaolchatha's replacement in time for the Fall ''A New Journey'' tour, which started on 10 October 2007 in Estero, FL. She was the first new member to join the group since its inception in 2004. She left Celtic Woman in November 2010 to continue performing in Ireland. On 14 February 2014, it was announced that Lynn would be returning for their Emerald tour in March while [[Lisa Lambe]] took a short 'leave of absence.' In early 2015, it was announced that Lynn would touring with the show again in April and May of that year for 10th Anniversary Tour. She has been a member of [[An\u00fana]] and continues to perform and record with the ensemble, most recently on their album \"Revelation\" (2015). In 2016 she and former Celtic Woman member [[Alex Sharpe]] formed the group  CaraNua.\n* '''Lisa Kelly''' {{main|Lisa Kelly}} Lisa Kelly is a singer of both classical and Celtic music. She was a founding member of the group.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.facebook.com/TheLisaKellyVoiceAcademy |title=The Lisa Kelly Voice Academy |publisher=Facebook |accessdate=10 March 2016}}{{Primary source inline|date=January 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=<!-- .entry-content --> <!-- .entry-meta --> |url=http://www.thelisakellyvoiceacademy.com |title=The Lisa Kelly Voice Academy |publisher=The Lisa Kelly Voice Academy |accessdate=10 March 2016}}</ref> During the ''A New Journey'' tour in 2008, Kelly took a break for the birth of her daughter and was replaced by [[Alex Sharpe]] In December 2011, Lisa announced that she would be taking another maternity leave and would not participate in the 2012 Believe Tour. She was replaced by [[Susan McFadden]]. In January 2013 Lisa announced her departure and moved to Peachtree City, Georgia, USA, where she announced the opening of '''The Lisa Kelly Voice Academy,''' indicating a switch from performing to teaching. The new voice academy is being run in conjunction with her husband Scott Porter, the former CEO of Celtic Woman Ltd.\n* '''Lisa Lambe''' {{main|Lisa Lambe}} Lisa Lambe is an Irish singer and actress. After the ''Songs From the Heart Tour,'' in November 2010, Lynn Hilary announced she was leaving the group to return to Ireland. Celtic Woman later announced that Lambe would join the group as part of the spring 2011 tour lineup. Lambe said that she was \"Delighted to be joining Celtic Woman! It is a privilege to be part of this amazing show and I am looking forward to it being an incredible experience.\" Lambe left the group in late 2014 to continue her solo career.<ref name=\":4\" />\n*'''Susan McFadden''' {{main|Susan McFadden}} Susan McFadden is an Irish actress and singer. She was named as a replacement for [[Lisa Kelly]], who was then going on maternity leave.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.CelticWoman.com/about/susan/|title=Susan \u2013 Celtic Woman \u2013 Irish Music Sensation|publisher=Celtic Woman|accessdate=10 March 2016}}</ref> She debuted with Celtic Woman in February at Nashville, Tennessee for the kickoff of the \"Believe\" North American Tour and continued with the European, Australian and South African Tours in 2012. She became a full-time member after Lisa Kelly announced her departure in January 2013. Susan announced her maternity leave on 12 August 2018.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/celticwoman/posts/10156594762912838|title=Celtic Woman|website=facebook.com|access-date=17 August 2018}}{{Primary source inline|date=January 2020}}</ref> Susan rejoined for a few shows in October 2019, filling in for Mairead Carlin while she recovered from appendicitis.{{cn|date=October 2019}} On 22 January 2020, it was announced that Susan will be performing in six shows for the spring tour in  the cities where Chlo\u00eb Agnew will not be appearing in.<ref name=\":6\" />\n* '''\u00c9abha McMahon''' {{main|\u00c9abha McMahon}} \u00c9abha was born in Dublin. She debuted with Celtic Woman in the album and DVD / TV special [[Celtic Woman: Destiny]] in 2015. On 22 January  2020, it was announced that McMahon was taking a leave from the group to work on her own projects. Chlo\u00eb Agnew returned to the group to take her place.<ref name=\":6\" /><ref name=\":5\" />\n*'''M\u00e9av N\u00ed Mhaolchatha''' {{Main|M\u00e9av N\u00ed Mhaolchatha}} M\u00e9av N\u00ed Mhaolchatha is an Irish singer, songwriter and recording artist specialising in the [[Music of Ireland|traditional music]] of her homeland. She was a member of [[An\u00fana]] from 1994 to 1998. She gained musical stardom as a founding member of the group in 2004. Her singing is a prominent element of Celtic Woman's first three albums, ''[[Celtic Woman (album)|Celtic Woman]],'' ''[[Celtic Woman: A Christmas Celebration]],'' and ''[[Celtic Woman: A New Journey]].'' In 2005, M\u00e9av was expecting her first child and took maternity leave and was replaced by Deirdre Shannon. In 2006, she returned to record the ''New Journey'' CD and DVD and toured extensively with the group in the US and Japan in 2006 and 2007. She has been featured in ''[[Celtic Woman: The Greatest Journey]] Essential Collection.'' In 2007, following the filming of Celtic Woman's Christmas DVD at [[The Helix (Dublin)|the Helix]], Dublin, she left the group to concentrate on her solo career. She appeared with Celtic Woman again when she featured as a guest soloist on their Christmas album ''[[Celtic Woman: Home for Christmas|Home for Christmas]].'' M\u00e9av was also featured in the Celtic Woman PBS special, \"Home for Christmas\", which was recorded on 7 August 2013. Before the recording of Destiny, she became Celtic Woman's vocal director and occasionally appears as a special guest/substitute.\n* '''M\u00e1ir\u00e9ad Nesbitt''' {{main|M\u00e1ir\u00e9ad Nesbitt}} M\u00e1ir\u00e9ad Nesbitt is an Irish classical and [[Celtic music]] performer, most notably as a violinist. In 2004, she was invited to play for a performance at the [[The Helix (Dublin)|Helix Theatre]] in Dublin, called \"Celtic Woman.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.MaireadNesbitt.com/news/CelticWoman.html|title=Celtic Woman|work=MaireadNesbitt.com|accessdate=25 February 2010}}</ref> She is featured on nine of the group's albums to date: ''[[Celtic Woman (album)|Celtic Woman]],'' ''[[Celtic Woman: A Christmas Celebration]],'' ''[[Celtic Woman: A New Journey]],'' ''[[Celtic Woman: The Greatest Journey]],'' ''[[Celtic Woman: Songs from the Heart]],'' ''[[Celtic Woman: Lullaby]],'' ''[[Celtic Woman: Believe]],'' and ''[[Celtic Woman: Home for Christmas]],'' and [[Destiny (Celtic Woman album)|Destiny]]. On 7 August 2016, it was announced that Nesbitt would be stepping away to focus on her own projects.<ref name=\":1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/CelticWoman/posts/10154398051527838:0|title=Celtic Woman Tour \u2013 Timeline {{!}} Facebook|website=www.facebook.com|access-date=7 August 2016}}</ref><ref name=\":2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/maireadnesbittcelticviolinist/posts/1757393424539932:0|title=M\u00e1ir\u00e9ad Nesbitt Celtic Violinist \u2013 Timeline {{!}} Facebook|website=www.facebook.com|access-date=7 August 2016}}</ref>\n* '''Deirdre Shannon''' {{main|Deirdre Shannon}} Deirdre Shannon is an Irish singer who has also toured with other [[Celtic music]] groups, such as [[An\u00fana]],<ref name=\"anuna-past\">{{cite web|url=http://www.anuna.ie/PastSingers.html |title=Past Members of An\u00fana 1997 to 2009 |work=Anuna.ie |year=2009 |accessdate=28 December 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101121051225/http://www.anuna.ie/PastSingers.html |archivedate=21 November 2010  }}</ref> and Celtic Thunder. She has also been a principal singer in the group, but was never featured in the studio DVDs. She joined the group as a stand-in during the first Celtic Woman tour in 2005 after M\u00e9av's first child was born.\n* '''Alex Sharpe''' {{main|Alex Sharpe}} Alex Sharpe is an Irish performer known for her musical roles. When founding member [[Lisa Kelly]] went on maternity leave, Sharpe became a temporary member in 2008. In 2009, Sharpe became a permanent member, in effect replacing [[\u00d3rla Fallon]]. She has toured with the group on their 2009 ''Isle of Hope'' tour, and recorded the CD and DVD for ''[[Celtic Woman: Songs from the Heart|Songs from the Heart]],'' released in January 2010.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.giantcenter.com/events/news_detail.php?ID=1061 |title=Giant Center in Hershey PA |website=Giantcenter.com |accessdate=10 March 2016}}</ref> The group toured North America from February to May 2010 on their 'Songs from the Heart' tour.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.irishemigrant.com/ie/go.asp?p=story&storyID=5663 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110713060320/http://www.irishemigrant.com/ie/go.asp?p=story&storyID=5663 |url-status=dead |archive-date=13 July 2011 |title=Celtic Woman sings from the heart |work=The Irish Emigrant |first=Melissa |last=Turtinen |accessdate=27 May 2010 }}</ref> After the tour finished, Sharpe announced she would be leaving to be with her family full-time.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://CelticWoman.com/trellis/alex_message |title=It has been a great joy... |first=Alex |last=Sharpe |year=2010 |accessdate=27 May 2010 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100529154543/http://www.celticwoman.com/trellis/alex_message |archivedate=29 May 2010 |url-status=dead }}</ref> In early 2015 it was announced that she would rejoin Celtic Woman for two months (May and June) of their Decade 10th Anniversary tour. In 2016, she and former Celtic Woman member [[Lynn Hilary]] formed the group  CaraNua. In 2018, Alex rejoined Celtic Woman for 12 shows of the North American Homecoming tour to fill in for [[Susan McFadden]] who went back to Ireland to attend a family emergency.\n* '''Hayley Westenra''' {{Main|Hayley Westenra}} Hayley Westenra is a New Zealand singer, [[classical crossover]] artist,<ref name=\"decca.com archives\">{{cite web|url=http://www.decca.com/artists/hayley-westenra-212 |title=Artists profile of Hayley Westenra |publisher=DECCA Records |accessdate=3 August 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110722034517/http://www.decca.com/artists/hayley-westenra-212 |archivedate=22 July 2011 }}</ref> songwriter and [[UNICEF]] Ambassador. She joined in August 2006 and was featured on ''Celtic Woman: A New Journey'' CD and DVD, toured on their 2007 Spring Tour, and was also featured on their DVD, ''The Greatest Journey: Essential Collection,'' released in 2008. After the Spring Tour ended, Hayley left to return to her solo career.\n\n== Membership ==\nThe original performers in Celtic Woman were [[Chlo\u00eb Agnew]], [[\u00d3rla Fallon]], [[Lisa Kelly]], [[M\u00e9av N\u00ed Mhaolchatha]], and [[M\u00e1ir\u00e9ad Nesbitt]]. During M\u00e9av's pregnancy in 2005, [[Deirdre Shannon]] was selected to fill her place during tours. M\u00e9av returned to the group in time to record ''A New Journey'' and tour for that album, coinciding with Deirdre's departure from the group in February 2006.\n\nThe second line-up change was announced on 6 September 2006, with the announcement that [[Hayley Westenra]] officially joined Celtic Woman on 24 August 2006.<ref name=\"CW211\">{{cite web |url=http://www.CelticWoman.com/viewSection.asp?idSection=211 |title=September 06 |work=CelticWoman.com |date=6 September 2006 |accessdate=13 February 2007 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070223143839/http://www.celticwoman.com/viewSection.asp?idSection=211 |archivedate=23 February 2007 |url-status=dead  }}</ref> As well as being featured on the album and DVD for ''A New Journey'', Hayley alternated with M\u00e9av during tour events to maintain the live five-person line-up.<ref name=\"CW218\">{{cite web |url=http://www.CelticWoman.com/viewSection.asp?idSection=218 |title=Hayley and M\u00e9av dates announced |work=CelticWoman.com |accessdate=13 February 2007 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070223143932/http://www.celticwoman.com/viewSection.asp?idSection=218 |archivedate=23 February 2007 |url-status=dead  }}</ref>\n\nOn 20 August 2007, M\u00e9av left Celtic Woman to focus on her solo career. M\u00e9av's replacement, [[Lynn Hilary]], made her first appearance on 10 October 2007 in [[Estero, Florida]], United States.<ref name=\"CW226\">{{cite web |url=http://www.CelticWoman.com/trellis/News/ |title=Welcoming Our New Celtic Woman |work=CelticWoman.com |date=20 August 2007 |accessdate=21 August 2007 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071012030930/http://www.celticwoman.com/trellis/News/ |archivedate=12 October 2007 |url-status=dead  }}</ref><ref name=\"meav-news1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.meav.com/home.htm |title=M\u00e9av Concert Tour Kicks off in New York |work=Meav.com |accessdate=3 December 2007 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071201073529/http://www.meav.com/home.htm |archivedate=1 December 2007 |url-status=dead  }}</ref>\n\nIn December 2007, Lisa Kelly, who was expecting her third child in 2008, took maternity leave from the group. [[Alex Sharpe]] filled her position on the ''A New Journey'' tour during this leave.<ref name=\"cw-sharpe1\">{{cite web |url=http://www.CelticWoman.com/ |title=And So... |work=CelticWoman.com |date=December 2007 |accessdate=9 December 2007 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071021040946/http://www.celticwoman.com/ |archivedate=21 October 2007 |url-status=dead  }}</ref>\n\nIt was announced on the group's website in 2009 that [[\u00d3rla Fallon]] was taking a full break to spend time with her family and to focus on recording a new solo album, and that as a result of this, Alex would be replacing \u00d3rla as a member of Celtic Woman.\n\nFor the 2009 ''Isle of Hope'' Tour, the group comprised vocalists Chlo\u00eb Agnew, [[Lynn Hilary]], Lisa Kelly, and [[Alex Sharpe]]; and fiddler [[M\u00e1ir\u00e9ad Nesbitt]]. This group completed the entire 2009 tour as well as the first leg of the ''[[Celtic Woman: Songs from the Heart|Songs from the Heart]]'' tour, from February to May 2010, with this line-up. After the tour ended, it was announced that Alex Sharpe would take a full-time break from Celtic Woman to spend time with her family.<ref name=\"Sharpe\">{{cite web |url=http://CelticWoman.com/trellis/alex_message |title=It has been a great joy... |work=CelticWoman.com |first=Alex |last=Sharpe |year=2010 |accessdate=27 May 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100529154543/http://www.celticwoman.com/trellis/alex_message |archivedate=29 May 2010 }}</ref>\n\nAfter the ''[[Celtic Woman: Songs from the Heart|Songs from the Heart]]'' tour, in November 2010, [[Lynn Hilary]] announced that she was leaving the group to return to Ireland.<ref name=\"Lynn-leaving\">{{cite web |url=http://www.CelticWoman.com/lynns-message/ |title=Celtic Woman: Lynn's Message |work=CelticWoman.com |date=November 2010 |accessdate=12 November 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101116134409/http://www.celticwoman.com/lynns-message/ |archivedate=16 November 2010 }}</ref> Singer and actress [[Lisa Lambe]] joined the group as a replacement for Lynn in early 2011.\n\nIn December 2011, Lisa Kelly announced that she would be taking maternity leave from the group after the \"Symphony Tour\" was over. The group's website announced in January 2012 that actress Susan McFadden would be filling in for Kelly until she returned to the group. However, Kelly announced the opening of \"The Lisa Kelly Voice Academy\" in Peachtree City, Georgia, in January 2013 say that she was moving on from performing to teaching. Susan has since become a full member of the line-up and appeared on the new Celtic Woman PBS special and DVD Emerald, released in early 2014.\n\nIn 2012, [[M\u00e9av N\u00ed Mhaolchatha]] returned briefly to Celtic Woman to record ''Celtic Woman: Home for Christmas'', the first time she had appeared with the group since her departure in 2007. She announced that she would return to the group again, temporary, in August 2013 to film the ''Celtic Woman: Home for Christmas'' PBS show and DVD.\n\nShortly before the \"Home for Christmas\" DVD show, [[Chlo\u00eb Agnew]] announced she would be taking a break from Celtic Woman to work on solo projects and was not featured in the PBS special. On 23 August 2013, it was announced that Derry-born singer [[Mairead Carlin|M\u00e1ir\u00e9ad Carlin]] would be taking Chlo\u00eb's place.\n\nShortly before the beginning of the Emerald Tour on 14 February 2014, management announced that [[Lisa Lambe]] would be leaving the tour at the beginning of March, with [[Lynn Hilary]] returning to take her place.  Lambe was slated to return during the summer, though no specific date was given.\n\nIn late 2014, Lambe shared she would be leaving Celtic Woman for a while to work on a solo album. She announced that her departure was permanent in early 2015 to promote her solo album and tour.<ref name=\":4\">{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.ie/entertainment/theatre-arts/out-of-hiding-lisa-lambe-is-finally-expressing-herself-31001154.html|title= Out of Hiding:Lisa Lambe is Finally Expressing Herself}}</ref> [[Lynn Hilary]] again returned and took Lambe's place. It was later announced both Hilary and [[Alex Sharpe]] would be returning for the Decade 10th Anniversary tour along with [[M\u00e9av N\u00ed Mhaolchatha|M\u00e9av]].\n\nOn 11 August 2015, it was announced that [[Eabha McMahon|\u00c9abha McMahon]] was joining Celtic Woman as a principal singer.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/CelticWoman/posts/10153523201587838:0|title=Celtic Woman Tour \u2013 Timeline {{!}} Facebook|website=www.facebook.com|access-date=7 August 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn 7 August 2016, it was announced that long-time member [[M\u00e1ir\u00e9ad Nesbitt]] was stepping away from Celtic Woman to focus on her own projects. [[Tara McNeill]], a violinist, harpist, and singer, was announced as a new member of Celtic Woman.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":2\" />\n\nFrom 11\u201323 March 2018, McFadden took a leave from the ''Celtic Woman: Homecoming'' tour to attend to a family emergency. Sharpe temporarily took McFadden's place in the lineup. McFadden returned to the tour on 24 March 2018 and remained with the group until the end of the tour.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/celticwoman/videos/10156211850207838/|title=Celtic Woman|website=facebook.com|access-date=24 March 2018}}{{Primary source inline|date=January 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/permalink.php?story_fbid=1743846588969645&id=212618112092508|title=Alex Sharpe|website=facebook.com|access-date=24 March 2018}}{{Primary source inline|date=January 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/susanmcfaddenofficial/posts/761238907415047|title=Susan McFadden|website=facebook.com|access-date=24 March 2018}}{{Primary source inline|date=January 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 12 August 2018, it was announced that McFadden, expecting her first child, was taking a leave from the group. On 16 August 2018, [[Megan Walsh]] was announced as a new member of the group, taking McFadden's place.<ref name=\":3\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/celticwoman/photos/a.164250352837/10156604105012838/?type=3|title=Celtic Woman|website=facebook.com|access-date=17 August 2018}}{{Primary source inline|date=January 2020}}</ref> In October 2019, [[Susan McFadden]] returned for a few shows on the groups European Tour while [[M\u00e1ir\u00e9ad Carlin]] recovered from appendicitis.\n\nOn 22 January 2020, it was announced that [[\u00c9abha McMahon]] was taking a leave from the group to pursue her own projects. [[Chlo\u00eb Agnew]] returned to the group for the US Celebration tour to take McMahon's place for the majority of the tour, and [[Susan McFadden]] would fill in for the dates Agnew would not be performing in.<ref name=\":6\" />\n\nWhen asked how the group members got along, founding former member [[Lisa Kelly]] responded,\n<blockquote>\n\"We get along because we're so different. [[Chlo\u00eb Agnew]] is hip, [[M\u00e9av N\u00ed Mhaolchatha]] is rational, [[Orla Fallon]] is angelic, and [[Mairead Nesbitt]] is energetic.\"<ref name=\"parade070523\">{{cite web|url=http://www.parade.com/articles/editions/2007/edition_06-03-2007/Personality_Parade |title=Personality Parade |work=Parade |first=Walter |last=Scott |date=23 May 2007 |accessdate=18 December 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071013004539/http://www.parade.com/articles/editions/2007/edition_06-03-2007/Personality_Parade |archivedate=13 October 2007 }}</ref>\n</blockquote>\nAccording to [[Chlo\u00eb Agnew]], the friendship between the vocalists was the number one question they were asked. She explained:\n<blockquote>\n\"I think people are always looking for a 'Desperate Housewives' story, that they all hate each other and nobody actually gets along. It's all for show. And the truth of the matter is, it's not. The reality is we do all get along. The five of us are like sisters, best friends.\"<ref name=\"harmoniously\">{{cite web|url=http://www.postcrescent.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20080402/APC05/80402152 |title=Celtic Woman members get along harmoniously |work=Post Crescent |accessdate=4 April 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140821205951/http://www.postcrescent.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=%2F20080402%2FAPC05%2F80402152 |archivedate=21 August 2014 }}</ref>\n</blockquote>\n===Member Timeline===\n<timeline>\nImageSize = width:1300 height:auto barincrement:25\nPlotArea = left:125 bottom:80 top:0 right:100\nAlignbars = justify\nDateFormat = dd/mm/yyyy\nPeriod = from:01/01/2004 till:31/12/2020\nTimeAxis = orientation:horizontal format:yyyy\n\nColors =\n  id:MaireadC        \tvalue:green\n  id:Eabha           \tvalue:gray(0.5)\n  id:Tara           \tvalue:green\n  id:Megan\t\tvalue:green\n  id:Susan           \tvalue:gray(0.5)\n  id:MaireadN        \tvalue:gray(0.5)\n  id:Chloe           \tvalue:green\n  id:Orla            \tvalue:gray(0.5)\n  id:Lynn            \tvalue:gray(0.5)\n  id:LisaK           \tvalue:gray(0.5)\n  id:LisaL           \tvalue:gray(0.5)\n  id:Deirdre\t\tvalue:gray(0.5)\n  id:Alex\t\tvalue:gray(0.5)\n  id:Hayley           \tvalue:gray(0.5)\n  id:Meav           \tvalue:gray(0.5)\n  id:bars               value:gray(0.9)\n\nBackgroundColors =  bars:bars\nScaleMajor = increment:1 start:2004\nScaleMinor = unit:year increment:1 start:2004\n\nBarData =\n  bar:MaireadC        \ttext:\"Mair\u00e9ad Carlin\"\n  bar:Tara\t\ttext:\"Tara McNeill\"\n  bar:Megan\t\ttext:\"Megan Walsh\"\n  bar:Chloe      \ttext:\"Chlo\u00eb Agnew\"\n\n  bar:Orla      \ttext:\"\u00d3rla Fallon\"\n  bar:Lynn        \ttext:\"Lynn Hilary\"\n  bar:LisaK     \ttext:\"Lisa Kelly\"\n  bar:LisaL     \ttext:\"Lisa Lambe\"\n  bar:Susan   \t\ttext:\"Susan McFadden\"\n  bar:Eabha          \ttext:\"\u00c9abha McMahon\"\n  bar:Meav       \ttext:\"M\u00e9av N\u00ed Mhaolchatha\"\n  bar:MaireadN         \ttext:\"M\u00e1ir\u00e9ad Nesbitt\"\n  bar:Deirdre      \ttex