ri that she will get her married to Ajay. The rest of the film is about how Ajay manages to save his marriage without hurting Lahari and how he gets Meenakshi back.\n\n==Cast==\n\n*[[Akkineni Nagarjuna|Nagarjuna Akkineni]] as Ajay\n*[[Simran (actress)|Simran]] as Meenakshi\n*[[Reema Sen]] as Lahari\n*[[Suman Ranganathan]] as Suma\n*[[Tanikella Bharani]]\n*[[Mallikarjuna Rao (actor)|Mallikarjuna Rao]]\n*[[M. S. Narayana]]\n*[[Sudha (Telugu actress)|Sudha]]\t\n*Raja Ravindra\n*Janardhan Maharshi\n*Ananth\n*Manorama\n*Rajitha\n*[[K. S. Ravikumar]] (cameo)\n\n==Soundtrack==\n{{Infobox album\n| name       = Bava Nachadu\n| type       = Soundtrack\n| artist     = [[M. M. Keeravani]]\n| cover      =\n| alt        =\n| released   = 2001\n| recorded   =2001\n| genre      = Soundtrack\n| length     = 30:37\n| label      = Supreme Music<br/>[[Aditya Music]]\n| producer   = M. M. Keeravani\n| prev_title = [[Student No.1]]\n| prev_year  = 2001\n| next_title = [[Akasa Veedhilo]]\n| next_year  = 2001\n}}\nThe music was composed by [[M. M. Keeravani]]. Music released on SUPREME Audio company.\n\n{{Track listing\n| collapsed =\n| headline = Track_List\n| extra_column = Singer(s)\n| total_length = 30:37\n| title1  = Anuragam Anuragamlo\n| lyrics1 = [[Chandrabose (lyricist)|Chandrabose]] \n| extra1  = [[Hariharan (singer)|Hariharan]], [[Sujatha Mohan|Sujatha]]\n| length1 = 5:22\n\n| title2  = Chandamama Chandamama\n| lyrics2 = Chandrabose\n| extra2  = [[Udit Narayan]], [[K. S. Chithra|Chitra]], [[Harini (singer)|Harini]]\n| length2 = 4:49\n\n| title3  = Matotundhi Magada\n| lyrics3 = [[Sirivennela Seetarama Sastry]]\n| extra3  = [[Shankar Mahadevan]], [[Anuradha Sriram]]\n| length3 = 5:31\n\n| title4  = Akka Bava Nachada\n| lyrics4 = [[Veturi Sundararama Murthy]]\n| extra4  = Harini\n| length4 = 4:34\n\n| title5  = Bang Bang\n| lyrics5 = Sirivennela Seetarama Sastry\n| extra5  = Shankar Mahadevan, [[Suneeta Rao]] \n| length5 = 5:09\n\n| title6  = Very Sexy\n| lyrics6 =Chandrabose\n| extra6  = Shankar Mahadevan, Ganga\n| length6 = 5:12\n}}\n\n==Reception==\nThe film received a mixed reception. Many declared the movie to be an outright drama with little or no logic at all. However, the movie fared well mainly due to the lack of any other quality cinema at that time and also of Simran's glamour and Nagarjuna's popularity.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb title|1604887|Bava Nachadu}}\n\n{{K. S. Ravikumar}}\n\n[[Category:2001 films]]\n[[Category:Telugu-language films]]\n[[Category:Indian films]]\n[[Category:Films directed by K. S. Ravikumar]]\n[[Category:Films scored by M. M. Keeravani]]\n[[Category:2000s Telugu-language films]]\n", "name_user": "Jellysandwich0", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bava_Nachadu"}
{"title_page": "Bhante Sujato", "text_new": "{{Infobox religious biography\n|image            = Ajahn Sujato.png\n|caption          = \n|birth_name       = Anthony Best\n|birth_date       = \n|birth_place      = \n|nationality      = Australian\n|religion         = [[Buddhism]]\n|school           = [[Theravada]]\n|title            = \n|dharma name = \n|location         = Sydney\n|education        = \n|occupation       = Bhikkhu (monk)\n|teacher          = [[Ajahn Brahm]]<ref name=\"door\"/>\n|website          = {{URL|https://lokanta.github.io}}\n}}\n\n{{Thai Forest Tradition}}\n'''Bhante Sujato''', known as '''Ajahn Sujato''' or '''Bhikkhu Sujato''' (born '''Anthony Best'''<ref name=\"door\">{{cite web|last=Lam|first=Raymond|title=An Afternoon with Ajahn Sujato: Personal Courage and Restoring the Sangha\u2019s Moral Purpose|url=https://www.buddhistdoor.net/features/an-afternoon-with-ajahn-sujato-personal-courage-and-restoring-the-sanghas-moral-purpose|publisher=Buddhistdoor Global|date=December 9, 2016|accessdate=September 7, 2019}}</ref>), is an Australian [[Theravada]] [[Buddhism|Buddhist]] [[Bhikkhu|monk]] who was ordained into in the [[Thai Forest Tradition|Thai forest lineage]] of [[Ajahn Chah]].<ref name=\"words\">{{cite web|title=\u2018Buddha\u2019s words a gift to humanity\u2019|url=http://www.dailynews.lk/2019/03/20/local/180746/%E2%80%98buddha%E2%80%99s-words-gift-humanity%E2%80%99|work=[[Daily News (Sri Lanka)|Daily News]]|date=March 20, 2019|accessdate=September 7, 2019}}</ref>\n\nA former musician<ref name=\"meeting\">{{cite web|title=A Meeting with Bhante Ajahn Sujato from Australia|url=https://www.sjp.ac.lk/buddhism/meeting-bhante-ajahn-sujato-australia/|publisher=[[University of Sri Jayewardenepura]]|date=May 30, 2018|accessdate=September 7, 2019}}</ref> with the Australian band [[Martha's Vineyard (band)|Martha's Vineyard]],<ref>{{cite web|title=Bhante Sujato|url=http://www.buddhachannel.tv/portail/spip.php?article9623|website=Buddhachannel|date=November 9, 2009|accessdate=September 8, 2019}}</ref> Sujato became a monk in 1994.<ref name=\"meeting\"/> He took [[Bhikkhu#Ordination|higher ordination]] in Thailand and lived there for years before returning to Australia.<ref name=\"meeting\"/> He spent several years at Bodhinyana Monastery in Western Australia before going on to found Santi Forest Monastery in 2003 where he served as the abbot. Following Bhante Sujato's wishes, Santi became a nun's monastery in 2012, and he returned to live in Bodhinyana.<ref name=\"bswa\">{{cite web|title=Bhante Sujato|url=https://bswa.org/teachers/bhante-sujato/|website=Buddhist Society of Western Australia|accessdate=September 7, 2019}}</ref>   \n\nIn 2005, Bhante Sujato co-founded the Buddhist website SuttaCentral<ref name=\"words\"/> along with Rod Bucknell and John Kelly, to provide access to early Buddhist texts in their original language and make translations available in modern languages.<ref>{{cite web|title=About SuttaCentral|url=https://suttacentral.net/about|website=SuttaCentral|accessdate=September 7, 2019}}</ref> After being unable to secure copyright-free digital translations of the [[Pali Canon]]for SuttaCentral, Bhante Sujato moved to the island of Chimei, off the cost of Taiwan,<ref name=\"door\"/><ref name=\"bswa\"/> to undertake the task of creating English translations of the four [[Nik\u0101ya]]s, living there from 2015 to 2018. These translations have since been published on SuttaCentral, and as free edition books.<ref>{{cite web|title=Bhante Sujato: \u201cTranslating a 2500 year-old Sacred Text for a Modern Audience\u201d|url=https://buddhiststudies.stanford.edu/events/bhante-sujato-translating-2500-year-old-sacred-text-modern-audience|publisher=[[Stanford University|Ho Center for Buddhist Studies]]|date=October 29, 2019 |accessdate=September 7, 2019}}</ref> \n\nIn 2019, Bhante Sujato moved to Sydney to establish Lokanta Vihara (the Monastery at the End of the World) with his long term student, Bhante Akaliko, to explore what it means to follow the Buddha\u2019s teachings in an era of climate change, globalised consumerism, and political turmoil.<ref name=\"lokanta\">{{cite web|title='About Us'|url=https://lokanta.github.io/|website=Lokanta Vihara|accessdate=April 20, 2020}}</ref> He is also involved with [[Engaged Buddhism]].<ref name=\"door\"/>\n\nBhante Sujato along with his teacher [[Ajahn Brahm]] were involved with [[Bhikkhuni#Re-establishing Bhikkhuni Ordination|Re-establishing Bhikkhuni Ordination]] in the Forest sangha of Ajahn Chah.<ref name=\"time\">{{cite web|author1= Thanissara|author2=Cintamani|author3=Jitindriya|title=The Time Has Come|url=https://www.lionsroar.com/the-time-has-come/|work=[[Lion's Roar (magazine)|Lion's Roar]]|date=August 25, 2010|accessdate=September 8, 2019}}</ref> Sujato along with other scholars such as Brahm and [[Bhikkhu Analayo]]<ref>{{cite journal|last=Analayo|first=Bhikkhu|authorlink=Bhikkhu Analayo|title=The Revival of the Bhikkhun\u012b Order and the Decline of the S\u0101sana|url=https://www.buddhismuskunde.uni-hamburg.de/pdf/5-personen/analayo/revival-bhikkhuni.pdf|journal=The Journal of Buddhist Ethics|volume=20|year=2013|ISSN=1076-9005}}</ref> had come to the conclusion that there was no valid reason the extinct bhikkhuni order couldn't be re-established.<ref name=\"door\"/><ref>{{cite web|last=Sujato|first=Ajahn|title=Bhikkhuni Ordination|url=https://bswa.org/teaching/bhukkhuni-ordination-ajahn-sujato/|website=Buddhist Society of Western Australia|accessdate=September 8, 2019}}</ref> The ordination ceremony led to [[Ajahn Brahm#Bhikkhuni ordination|Brahm's expulsion]] from the Thai Forest Lineage of Ajahn Chah.<ref name=\"time\"/>\n\n==Bibliography==\n*{{citation|last=Sujato|first=Bhante|title=A History of Mindfulness|publisher=Santipada|year=2012|url=http://santifm.org/santipada/wp-content/uploads/2012/08/A_History_of_Mindfulness_Bhikkhu_Sujato.pdf|ISBN=9781921842108}}\n*{{citation|last=Sujato|first=Bhante|title=A Swift Pair of Messengers: Calm with Insight in the Buddha\u2019s Words |publisher=Santipada|year=2012|ISBN=9781921842023}}\n*{{citation|last=Sujato|first=Bhante|title=Sects & Sectarianism: The Origins of Buddhist Schools |publisher=Santipada|year=2012|ISBN=9781921842085}}\n*{{citation|last=Sujato|first=Bhante|title=Bhikkhuni Vinaya Studies: Research and Reflections on Monastic Discipline for Buddhist Nuns |publisher=Santipada|year=2012|ISBN=9781921842146}}\n*{{citation|last=Sujato|first=Bhante|title=White Bones Red Rot Black Snakes|url=http://santifm.org/santipada/wp-content/uploads/2012/08/wbrrbsSCREENopt.pdf||publisher=Santipada|year=2012|ISBN=9781921842030}}\n*{{citation|last1=Sujato|first1=Bhante|last2=Brahmali|first2=Bhikkhu|title=The Authenticity of the Early Buddhist Texts|url=https://ocbs.org/wp-content/uploads/2015/09/authenticity.pdf|year=2015|publisher=Chroniker Press|ISBN=9781312911505}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://sujato.wordpress.com Sujato's Blog]\n*[http://podcast.bswa.org/category/bhante-sujato/ Dhamma talks by Ajahn Sujato]\n*[https://lokanta.github.io/ Lokanta Vihara website]\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{Buddhism topics}}\n{{Modern Buddhist writers}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sujato, Bhante}}\n[[Category:Theravada Buddhism writers]]\n[[Category:Converts to Buddhism]]\n[[Category:Buddhist writers]]\n[[Category:Theravada Buddhist monks]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Nonviolence advocates]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox religious biography\n|image            = Ajahn Sujato.png\n|caption          = \n|birth_name       = Anthony Best\n|birth_date       = \n|birth_place      = \n|nationality      = Australian\n|religion         = [[Buddhism]]\n|school           = [[Theravada]]\n|title            = \n|dharma name = \n|location         = Sydney\n|education        = \n|occupation       = Bhikkhu (monk)\n|teacher          = [[Ajahn Brahm]]<ref name=\"door\"/>\n|website          = {{URL|https://lokanta.github.io}}\n}}\n\n{{Thai Forest Tradition}}\n'''Bhante Sujato''', known as '''Ajahn Sujato''' or '''Bhikkhu Sujato''' (born '''Anthony Best'''<ref name=\"door\">{{cite web|last=Lam|first=Raymond|title=An Afternoon with Ajahn Sujato: Personal Courage and Restoring the Sangha\u2019s Moral Purpose|url=https://www.buddhistdoor.net/features/an-afternoon-with-ajahn-sujato-personal-courage-and-restoring-the-sanghas-moral-purpose|publisher=Buddhistdoor Global|date=December 9, 2016|accessdate=September 7, 2019}}</ref>), is an Australian [[Theravada]] [[Buddhism|Buddhist]] [[Bhikkhu|monk]] who was ordained into in the [[Thai Forest Tradition|Thai forest lineage]] of [[Ajahn Chah]].<ref name=\"words\">{{cite web|title=\u2018Buddha\u2019s words a gift to humanity\u2019|url=http://www.dailynews.lk/2019/03/20/local/180746/%E2%80%98buddha%E2%80%99s-words-gift-humanity%E2%80%99|work=[[Daily News (Sri Lanka)|Daily News]]|date=March 20, 2019|accessdate=September 7, 2019}}</ref>\n\nA former musician<ref name=\"meeting\">{{cite web|title=A Meeting with Bhante Ajahn Sujato from Australia|url=https://www.sjp.ac.lk/buddhism/meeting-bhante-ajahn-sujato-australia/|publisher=[[University of Sri Jayewardenepura]]|date=May 30, 2018|accessdate=September 7, 2019}}</ref> with the Australian band [[Martha's Vineyard (band)|Martha's Vineyard]],<ref>{{cite web|title=Bhante Sujato|url=http://www.buddhachannel.tv/portail/spip.php?article9623|website=Buddhachannel|date=November 9, 2009|accessdate=September 8, 2019}}</ref> Sujato became a monk in 1994.<ref name=\"meeting\"/> He took [[Bhikkhu#Ordination|higher ordination]] in Thailand and lived there for years before returning to Australia.<ref name=\"meeting\"/> He spent several years at Bodhinyana Monastery in Western Australia before going on to found Santi Forest Monastery in 2003 where he served as the abbot. Following Bhante Sujato's wishes, Santi became a nun's monastery in 2012, and he returned to live in Bodhinyana.<ref name=\"bswa\">{{cite web|title=Bhante Sujato|url=https://bswa.org/teachers/bhante-sujato/|website=Buddhist Society of Western Australia|accessdate=September 7, 2019}}</ref>   \n\nIn 2005, Bhante Sujato co-founded the Buddhist website SuttaCentral<ref name=\"words\"/> along with Rod Bucknell and John Kelly, to provide access to early Buddhist texts in their original language and make translations available in modern languages.<ref>{{cite web|title=About SuttaCentral|url=https://suttacentral.net/about|website=SuttaCentral|accessdate=September 7, 2019}}</ref> After being unable to secure copyright-free digital translations of the [[Pali Canon]]for SuttaCentral, Bhante Sujato moved to the island of Chimei, off the cost of Taiwan,<ref name=\"door\"/><ref name=\"bswa\"/> to undertake the task of creating English translations of the the four [[Nik\u0101ya]]s, living there from 2015 to 2018. These translations have since been published on SuttaCentral, and as free edition books.<ref>{{cite web|title=Bhante Sujato: \u201cTranslating a 2500 year-old Sacred Text for a Modern Audience\u201d|url=https://buddhiststudies.stanford.edu/events/bhante-sujato-translating-2500-year-old-sacred-text-modern-audience|publisher=[[Stanford University|Ho Center for Buddhist Studies]]|date=October 29, 2019 |accessdate=September 7, 2019}}</ref> \n\nIn 2019, Bhante Sujato moved to Sydney to establish Lokanta Vihara (the Monastery at the End of the World) with his long term student, Bhante Akaliko, to explore what it means to follow the Buddha\u2019s teachings in an era of climate change, globalised consumerism, and political turmoil.<ref name=\"lokanta\">{{cite web|title='About Us'|url=https://lokanta.github.io/|website=Lokanta Vihara|accessdate=April 20, 2020}}</ref> He is also involved with [[Engaged Buddhism]].<ref name=\"door\"/>\n\nBhante Sujato along with his teacher [[Ajahn Brahm]] were involved with [[Bhikkhuni#Re-establishing Bhikkhuni Ordination|Re-establishing Bhikkhuni Ordination]] in the Forest sangha of Ajahn Chah.<ref name=\"time\">{{cite web|author1= Thanissara|author2=Cintamani|author3=Jitindriya|title=The Time Has Come|url=https://www.lionsroar.com/the-time-has-come/|work=[[Lion's Roar (magazine)|Lion's Roar]]|date=August 25, 2010|accessdate=September 8, 2019}}</ref> Sujato along with other scholars such as Brahm and [[Bhikkhu Analayo]]<ref>{{cite journal|last=Analayo|first=Bhikkhu|authorlink=Bhikkhu Analayo|title=The Revival of the Bhikkhun\u012b Order and the Decline of the S\u0101sana|url=https://www.buddhismuskunde.uni-hamburg.de/pdf/5-personen/analayo/revival-bhikkhuni.pdf|journal=The Journal of Buddhist Ethics|volume=20|year=2013|ISSN=1076-9005}}</ref> had come to the conclusion that there was no valid reason the extinct bhikkhuni order couldn't be re-established.<ref name=\"door\"/><ref>{{cite web|last=Sujato|first=Ajahn|title=Bhikkhuni Ordination|url=https://bswa.org/teaching/bhukkhuni-ordination-ajahn-sujato/|website=Buddhist Society of Western Australia|accessdate=September 8, 2019}}</ref> The ordination ceremony led to [[Ajahn Brahm#Bhikkhuni ordination|Brahm's expulsion]] from the Thai Forest Lineage of Ajahn Chah.<ref name=\"time\"/>\n\n==Bibliography==\n*{{citation|last=Sujato|first=Bhante|title=A History of Mindfulness|publisher=Santipada|year=2012|url=http://santifm.org/santipada/wp-content/uploads/2012/08/A_History_of_Mindfulness_Bhikkhu_Sujato.pdf|ISBN=9781921842108}}\n*{{citation|last=Sujato|first=Bhante|title=A Swift Pair of Messengers: Calm with Insight in the Buddha\u2019s Words |publisher=Santipada|year=2012|ISBN=9781921842023}}\n*{{citation|last=Sujato|first=Bhante|title=Sects & Sectarianism: The Origins of Buddhist Schools |publisher=Santipada|year=2012|ISBN=9781921842085}}\n*{{citation|last=Sujato|first=Bhante|title=Bhikkhuni Vinaya Studies: Research and Reflections on Monastic Discipline for Buddhist Nuns |publisher=Santipada|year=2012|ISBN=9781921842146}}\n*{{citation|last=Sujato|first=Bhante|title=White Bones 